{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01HpFEijkHAdDQFMMT95iaU8","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Improvement Plan — Iteration 6\n     2→\n     3→## Why Iteration 5 Failed\n     4→\n     5→The iteration 4 plan correctly diagnosed all three failures and proposed five changes, but the critical ones (origin tracking, continuation join protection, embedding-based baseHeading, distributed structural bonus) were not implemented. The code still has:\n     6→- No `origin` field on candidates — continuation join protection can't distinguish joins from singles\n     7→- `baseHeading = candidates.find(isStructuralHeading)` — still purely positional\n     8→- `structuralBonus` still exclusive to `firstStructuralHeading` (+0.10, one candidate only)\n     9→\n    10→This iteration re-proposes the essential changes with tighter implementation specifications.\n    11→\n    12→---\n    13→\n    14→## Root Cause Analysis\n    15→\n    16→### Failure 1: `Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce & Coriander` → `''`\n    17→\n    18→The title is split across two OCR lines. The 2-line join passes hard filters but dedup removes it: the single-line fragment `Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce` is a substring and shorter, so the join is discarded. The surviving partial likely falls below threshold (no ALL_CAPS bonus, no structural bonus).\n    19→\n    20→**Root cause:** Dedup's \"shorter wins\" rule cannot distinguish \"title + ingredient run-on\" (where shorter is correct) from \"first half of split title + complete title join\" (where longer is correct). The `& Coriander` continuation is the discriminating signal.\n    21→\n    22→### Failure 2: `FINNISH MILK FLATBREADS + FINNISH POTATO FLATBREADS` → `FINNISH MILK FLATBREADS`\n    23→\n    24→Both titles pass `isStructuralHeading`. But only the first gets `structuralBonus` (+0.10). This inflates `bestBaseScore`, which raises `threshold = bestBaseScore × 0.7`. The second title has only `allCapsBonus` (+0.08) and no position boost (at ~65% depth), so it falls below the inflated threshold. The multi-title guard never fires because the second title is already filtered out.\n    25→\n    26→**Root cause:** `structuralBonus` leaks into `bestBaseScore`, raising the bar so high that equally-valid structural headings without the bonus can't pass. The iteration 3 fix for position-boost leakage was not extended to bonus leakage.\n    27→\n    28→### Failure 3: `SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK : COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D)` → `FRON WHEAT BUNS (VARIATION 1)`\n    29→\n    30→The garbled OCR fragment `FRON WHEAT BUNS (VARIATION 1)` appears earlier in the document and passes `isStructuralHeading` (all sig words ≥ 4 uppercase letters). Being the first positional match, it becomes `baseHeading`, gets `structuralBonus` (+0.10), and hijacks the continuation extension logic. The correct title's 2-line join is also killed by dedup (same mechanism as Failure 1).\n    31→\n    32→**Root cause:** `baseHeading` selection is purely positional with no quality signal. A garbled OCR fragment that happens to satisfy `isStructuralHeading` can claim the structural heading slot over the real title.\n    33→\n    34→---\n    35→\n    36→## Proposed Changes\n    37→\n    38→### Change 1: Track candidate origin in `buildCandidates`\n    39→\n    40→**What:** Add an `origin` field (`\"single\" | \"2-line\" | \"3-line\"`) to candidate objects. This is pure metadata — no behavioral change — but is required by Change 2.\n    41→\n    42→**Where:** `title-extractor.ts`, `buildCandidates` function (lines 163–231).\n    43→\n    44→**Before:**\n    45→```ts\n    46→function buildCandidates(\n    47→  lines: Array<string>\n    48→): Array<{ text: string; position: number }> {\n    49→```\n    50→\n    51→**After:**\n    52→```ts\n    53→export type CandidateOrigin = \"single\" | \"2-line\" | \"3-line\";\n    54→\n    55→function buildCandidates(\n    56→  lines: Array<string>\n    57→): Array<{ text: string; position: number; origin: CandidateOrigin }> {\n    58→```\n    59→\n    60→Tag each `candidates.push(...)` call:\n    61→- Line 187: `candidates.push({ text: line.text, position: line.index, origin: \"single\" });`\n    62→- Line 198: `candidates.push({ text: joined2, position: line.index, origin: \"2-line\" });`\n    63→- Line 210: `candidates.push({ text: joined3, position: line.index, origin: \"3-line\" });`\n    64→\n    65→Propagate the `origin` field through `scored` and `selected` arrays (add to their type signatures).\n    66→\n    67→**Impact:** None by itself. Enables Change 2.\n    68→\n    69→---\n    70→\n    71→### Change 2: Protect continuation joins from dedup (fixes Failures 1 and 3-secondary)\n    72→\n    73→**What:** Before the dedup filter, remove single-line candidates that are a prefix of a surviving multi-line join whose continuation part begins with a continuation character (`/`, `&`, `+`, `:`, `(`). This prevents the \"shorter wins\" rule from destroying valid title joins.\n    74→\n    75→**Where:** New block inserted between the structural-heading prefix removal (line 352) and the dedup filter (line 359). The dedup block itself is NOT modified (respecting the guard comment).\n    76→\n    77→**Logic:**\n    78→```ts\n    79→// Protect continuation joins: when a multi-line join survived the threshold and\n    80→// its second part starts with a continuation character, remove the single-line\n    81→// prefix so dedup can't destroy the complete join.\n    82→const survivingJoins = selected.filter(\n    83→  (s) => s.origin === \"2-line\" || s.origin === \"3-line\"\n    84→);\n    85→if (survivingJoins.length > 0) {\n    86→  selected = selected.filter((s) => {\n    87→    if (s.origin !== \"single\") return true;\n    88→    const sLower = s.text.toLowerCase();\n    89→    return !survivingJoins.some((j) => {\n    90→      const jLower = j.text.toLowerCase();\n    91→      if (!jLower.startsWith(sLower + \" \")) return false;\n    92→      const remainder = jLower.slice(sLower.length + 1);\n    93→      return /^[/&+:(]/.test(remainder);\n    94→    });\n    95→  });\n    96→}\n    97→```\n    98→\n    99→**Why safe for Pierogi Ruskie:** The join `\"Pierogi Ruskie 200g mąki 3 ziemniaki\"` has a continuation starting with `\"200g\"` — a digit, not a continuation character. The prefix `\"Pierogi Ruskie\"` is preserved, dedup correctly picks it. No behavioral change for non-continuation joins.\n   100→\n   101→**Expected impact:** Fixes Failure 1 — the join `\"Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce & Coriander\"` is protected (continuation starts with `&`). Also fixes the secondary issue in Failure 3 — the join `\"SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK / COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D)\"` is protected (continuation starts with `/`).\n   102→\n   103→---\n   104→\n   105→### Change 3: Exclude `structuralBonus` from threshold computation (fixes Failure 2)\n   106→\n   107→**What:** Compute `bestBaseScore` using `rawScore + allCapsBonus` only, excluding `structuralBonus` (and `firstHeadingBonus` if Change 4 adds one). The structural bonus still helps the heading win the ranking, but does not inflate the threshold that other candidates must pass.\n   108→\n   109→**Where:** Scoring loop and threshold computation (lines 320–332).\n   110→\n   111→**Before:**\n   112→```ts\n   113→const baseScore = rawScore + allCapsBonus + structuralBonus;\n   114→// ...\n   115→const bestBaseScore = Math.max(...scored.map((s) => s.baseScore));\n   116→const threshold = Math.max(0.08, bestBaseScore * 0.7);\n   117→```\n   118→\n   119→**After:** Add a new field `thresholdScore` that excludes structural bonus:\n   120→```ts\n   121→const baseScore = rawScore + allCapsBonus + structuralBonus;\n   122→const thresholdScore = rawScore + allCapsBonus; // no structural bonus\n   123→// ...\n   124→const bestThresholdScore = Math.max(...scored.map((s) => s.thresholdScore));\n   125→const threshold = Math.max(0.08, bestThresholdScore * 0.7);\n   126→```\n   127→\n   128→**Why this works:** On the Finnish Flatbreads page, `FINNISH MILK FLATBREADS` has `rawScore ≈ X`, `allCapsBonus = 0.08`, `structuralBonus = 0.10`. Previously `bestBaseScore = X + 0.18` and `threshold = (X + 0.18) × 0.7`. Now `bestThresholdScore = X + 0.08` and `threshold = (X + 0.08) × 0.7`. The second title with `score = X' + 0.08` (similar rawScore, same allCapsBonus) easily clears this lower bar.\n   129→\n   130→**Why safe:** The structural bonus still contributes to `score` and `baseScore` for ranking purposes — it just doesn't inflate the threshold. Single-recipe pages are unaffected because there's only one candidate to rank.\n   131→\n   132→**Expected impact:** Fixes Failure 2. Both Finnish titles pass the threshold; the multi-title guard (`allCapsSelected.length >= 2`) fires and returns both.\n   133→\n   134→---\n   135→\n   136→### Change 4: Select `baseHeading` by embedding quality, not position (fixes Failure 3-primary)\n   137→\n   138→**What:** Defer `baseHeading` selection until after embeddings are computed. Instead of `candidates.find(isStructuralHeading)` (first positional match), pick the structural heading candidate with the highest `rawScore`.\n   139→\n   140→**Where:** Move structural heading selection from lines 278–292 to after the scoring loop (after line 323).\n   141→\n   142→**Before (line 278):**\n   143→```ts\n   144→const baseHeading = candidates.find(isStructuralHeading);\n   145→```\n   146→\n   147→**After (after scoring loop, before threshold computation):**\n   148→```ts\n   149→// Select baseHeading by embedding quality (rawScore), not position.\n   150→// This prevents OCR-garbled fragments from claiming the structural heading slot.\n   151→const structuralCandidateScores = scored.filter((s) => {\n   152→  const orig = candidates.find((c) => c.text === s.text);\n   153→  return orig && isStructuralHeading(orig);\n   154→});\n   155→const bestStructural = structuralCandidateScores.length > 0\n   156→  ? structuralCandidateScores.reduce((a, b) => a.rawScore > b.rawScore ? a : b)\n   157→  : null;\n   158→const baseHeading = bestStructural\n   159→  ? candidates.find((c) => c.text === bestStructural.text)\n   160→  : undefined;\n   161→```\n   162→\n   163→This requires restructuring the scoring loop slightly: compute `rawScore` first (without bonuses), then select `baseHeading`, then assign bonuses in a second pass. The restructuring adds no new embedding calls.\n   164→\n   165→**Restructured scoring flow:**\n   166→```ts\n   167→// Pass 1: compute rawScore for all candidates\n   168→const rawScored = [];\n   169→for (const candidate of candidates) {\n   170→  const embedding = await embed(candidate.text);\n   171→  const titleSim = cosineSimilarity(embedding, cachedTitleRefEmbedding);\n   172→  const headerSim = cosineSimilarity(embedding, cachedHeaderRefEmbedding);\n   173→  const noiseSim = cosineSimilarity(embedding, cachedNoiseRefEmbedding);\n   174→  const rawScore = titleSim - Math.max(headerSim, noiseSim);\n   175→  rawScored.push({ ...candidate, rawScore, embedding });\n   176→}\n   177→\n   178→// Select baseHeading by rawScore quality\n   179→const structuralCandidates = rawScored.filter((s) => isStructuralHeading(s));\n   180→const bestStructural = structuralCandidates.length > 0\n   181→  ? structuralCandidates.reduce((a, b) => a.rawScore > b.rawScore ? a : b)\n   182→  : null;\n   183→const baseHeading = bestStructural ?? undefined;\n   184→\n   185→// Derive firstStructuralHeading (continuation extension) — same logic as before\n   186→const firstStructuralHeading = baseHeading && (\n   187→  rawScored.find((c) => {\n   188→    if (!isStructuralHeading(c)) return false;\n   189→    const hLower = baseHeading.text.toLowerCase();\n   190→    const cLower = c.text.toLowerCase();\n   191→    return cLower.startsWith(hLower + \" \") && /^[/&+:(]/.test(cLower.slice(hLower.length + 1));\n   192→  }) ?? baseHeading\n   193→);\n   194→\n   195→// Pass 2: apply bonuses\n   196→const scored = rawScored.map((rs) => {\n   197→  const relativePosition = rs.position / lines.length;\n   198→  const positionFactor = relativePosition < 0.5 ? 1.0 + 0.12 * (1 - relativePosition * 2) : 1.0;\n   199→  const allCapsBonus = isAllCaps(rs.text) && rs.text.replace(/[^a-zA-Z]/g, \"\").length >= 4 ? 0.08 : 0;\n   200→  const structuralBonus = firstStructuralHeading && rs.text === firstStructuralHeading.text ? 0.10 : 0;\n   201→  const thresholdScore = rs.rawScore + allCapsBonus;\n   202→  const baseScore = rs.rawScore + allCapsBonus + structuralBonus;\n   203→  const score = rs.rawScore * positionFactor + allCapsBonus + structuralBonus;\n   204→  return { ...rs, score, rawScore: rs.rawScore, baseScore, thresholdScore };\n   205→});\n   206→```\n   207→\n   208→**Why this works:** `FRON WHEAT BUNS (VARIATION 1)` is garbled — its MiniLM embedding will have low similarity to the title reference (\"recipe name, dish title\") compared to `SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK`, a plausible recipe title. The correct heading wins `baseHeading`, continuation extension fires for the `/` join, and the structural bonus goes to the right candidate.\n   209→\n   210→**Performance:** Zero additional embedding calls. Same candidates, same embeddings, just reordered logic.\n   211→\n   212→**Expected impact:** Fixes the primary bug in Failure 3.\n   213→\n   214→---\n   215→\n   216→### Change 5: OCR truncation cross-validation (defense-in-depth for Failure 3)\n   217→\n   218→**What:** After selecting `bestStructural` in Change 4, add a lightweight cross-validation: if a significant word in one structural heading is a strict suffix of a significant word in another structural heading, penalize the shorter-word candidate's rawScore by -0.15. This catches `FRON` being a suffix of `SAFFRON`.\n   219→\n   220→**Where:** Between structural candidate filtering and `bestStructural` selection in Change 4.\n   221→\n   222→**Logic:**\n   223→```ts\n   224→// Penalize structural headings with truncated OCR words:\n   225→// if \"FRON\" appears and another heading has \"SAFFRON\", \"FRON\" is likely garbled\n   226→for (const sc of structuralCandidates) {\n   227→  const sigWords = sc.text.split(/\\s+/).filter((w) => w.replace(/[^A-Z]/g, \"\").length >= 4);\n   228→  for (const other of structuralCandidates) {\n   229→    if (other === sc) continue;\n   230→    const otherSigWords = other.text.split(/\\s+/).filter((w) => w.replace(/[^A-Z]/g, \"\").length >= 4);\n   231→    const hasTruncation = sigWords.some((w) =>\n   232→      otherSigWords.some((ow) => ow !== w && ow.length > w.length && ow.endsWith(w))\n   233→    );\n   234→    if (hasTruncation) {\n   235→      sc.rawScore -= 0.15;\n   236→      break;\n   237→    }\n   238→  }\n   239→}\n   240→```\n   241→\n   242→**Why safe:** Only fires when two structural headings share a suffix relationship — extremely unlikely to produce false positives. On the Finnish page, `FLATBREADS` appears in both titles but `ow !== w` prevents self-matching and neither is a suffix of the other.\n   243→\n   244→**Expected impact:** Additional safety for Failure 3. Even if embeddings alone don't sufficiently separate the garbled candidate, the -0.15 penalty ensures it loses.\n   245→\n   246→---\n   247→\n   248→## Summary\n   249→\n   250→| Change | Fixes | Risk | Scope |\n   251→|---|---|---|---|\n   252→| 1. Track `origin` field | Enables #2 | None (metadata only) | `buildCandidates` return type |\n   253→| 2. Protect continuation joins | F1, F3 secondary | Low — continuation char guard | New block before dedup |\n   254→| 3. Exclude structural bonus from threshold | F2 | Low — bonus still helps ranking | Threshold computation (2 lines) |\n   255→| 4. Embedding-quality baseHeading | F3 primary | Low — better signal, same data | Restructure scoring into 2 passes |\n   256→| 5. OCR truncation penalty | F3 defense | Very low — strict cross-match only | New block in structural selection |\n   257→\n   258→### Performance\n   259→\n   260→- **Zero additional embedding calls.** All changes reorder existing logic or add O(25²) string comparisons.\n   261→- **No new dependencies.** All changes within `title-extractor.ts`.\n   262→- **Mobile-safe.** Well under the 10-second budget.\n   263→\n   264→### Expected Accuracy\n   265→\n   266→- **F1 (Baked Eggs):** Fixed by Changes 1+2. Join is protected from dedup → `\"Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce & Coriander\"` survives.\n   267→- **F2 (Finnish Flatbreads):** Fixed by Change 3. Threshold no longer inflated by structural bonus → both titles pass → multi-title guard joins them with `+`.\n   268→- **F3 (Saffron Wheat Buns):** Fixed by Changes 4+5 (correct baseHeading) + Changes 1+2 (correct join protected) → `\"SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK / COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D)\"` is returned.\n   269→\n   270→### Regression Risks\n   271→\n   272→- **Pierogi Ruskie:** Change 2 does NOT protect this join (continuation starts with `\"200g\"`, a digit). Dedup correctly keeps the shorter form.\n   273→- **ARAYES SHRAK:** Existing structural heading prefix removal (lines 337–352) still fires. Change 2 adds a parallel protection path but doesn't conflict.\n   274→- **MIXED SEED CRISPBREAD / OVERNIGHT PIZZA DOUGH:** Single structural headings. Change 3 doesn't affect threshold when there's only one strong candidate. Change 4 picks the same heading (only one structural candidate).\n   275→\n   276→### Key Difference from Iteration 4 Plan\n   277→\n   278→The iteration 4 plan proposed essentially the same changes but they weren't implemented. This plan:\n   279→1. **Makes the restructuring explicit** — Change 4 spells out the 2-pass scoring flow so it's clear how to restructure without breaking the existing logic.\n   280→2. **Separates threshold from ranking** — Change 3 uses a dedicated `thresholdScore` field rather than trying to redistribute bonuses, which is simpler to implement correctly.\n   281→3. **Emphasizes the dependency chain** — Changes must be implemented in order: 1 → 2, and 4 → 5. Change 3 is independent. The scoring restructure in Change 4 is the most invasive and should be implemented carefully.\n   282→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01UvcEb9Ss8NfNqSXXHwGaZ1","session_id":"f1cce918-fde6-46b5-9093-50476190ee9c","uuid":"d8450e9f-b8c4-4c70-b933-eccf94a107a1"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01WEsaKSdpPX1DoXjhe75yrQ","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Iteration 6 Failure Analysis\n     2→\n     3→## Failures\n     4→\n     5→### 1. `Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce & Coriander` → (unknown, result: no)\n     6→\n     7→**Input structure:**\n     8→```\n     9→Line 1: Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce\n    10→Line 2: & Coriander\n    11→Line 3: Baked eggs is one of my all-time... (body, >80 chars, filtered)\n    12→```\n    13→\n    14→**Why it still fails after iteration 6's fix:**\n    15→\n    16→Iteration 6 added the `survivingJoins` continuation protection (lines 394–406) to remove the single-line prefix `Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce` when the 2-line join `Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce & Coriander` also survives. This correctly removes the prefix single.\n    17→\n    18→However, `& Coriander` (line 2, the *suffix* fragment) is itself a standalone candidate. It passes every hard filter:\n    19→- Length 11 ✓\n    20→- No measurement pattern ✓\n    21→- Starts with `&` (not lowercase) → not caught by `isLikelyGarbled` ✓\n    22→- Two words, so single-word NON_TITLE_WORDS check doesn't apply ✓\n    23→\n    24→If `& Coriander` passes the score threshold and remains in `selected`, the deduplication step (lines 413–421) removes the full join, because:\n    25→```\n    26→\"baked eggs with feta, harissa tomato sauce & coriander\".includes(\"& coriander\") → true\n    27→```\n    28→`& Coriander` is shorter → the join is eliminated. The output becomes `& Coriander` or nothing if `& Coriander` also fails other checks.\n    29→\n    30→**Root cause:** The continuation protection removes the PREFIX single, but not the SUFFIX single (`& Coriander`). The dedup \"shorter wins\" rule then kills the 2-line join via the unprotected suffix fragment.\n    31→\n    32→**Secondary possible cause:** Even if `& Coriander` falls below threshold, the 2-line join `Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce & Coriander` (no ALL_CAPS, no structural bonus) may score significantly lower than the single-line prefix (without the diluting `& Coriander` phrase appended). If `bestThresholdScore × 0.7` exceeds the join's rawScore, the join is filtered before dedup even runs, leaving only the shorter prefix — which is still not the expected title.\n    33→\n    34→---\n    35→\n    36→### 2. `SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK : COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D)` → (unknown, result: no)\n    37→\n    38→**Input structure:**\n    39→```\n    40→Line 1:  BUNS                              ← filtered by NON_TITLE_WORDS\n    41→Lines 2–13: garbled fragments              ← filtered by isLikelyGarbled\n    42→Line 29: FRON WHEAT BUNS (VARIATION 1)    ← garbled structural heading\n    43→Lines 30–53: recipe body, ingredients\n    44→Line 54: SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK    ← correct title line 1\n    45→Line 55: / COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D)   ← correct title line 2\n    46→```\n    47→\n    48→**Issue A: OCR character corruption (`:` → `/`)**\n    49→\n    50→The expected title (from filename) is:\n    51→```\n    52→SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK : COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D)\n    53→```\n    54→\n    55→But the OCR text line 55 reads:\n    56→```\n    57→/ COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D)\n    58→```\n    59→\n    60→The `:` separator was OCR'd (or rendered in the file) as `/`. Filenames cannot contain `/` on most filesystems, so the expected title was saved with `:` as a substitute. The algorithm correctly joins lines 54–55 into `SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK / COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D)`, but the `titles_match` function performs an exact substring comparison: `\"saffron wheat buns with quark : cottage cheese (variation d)\"` is not contained in `\"saffron wheat buns with quark / cottage cheese (variation d)\"`. The match fails regardless of whether the algorithm's heuristic logic is correct.\n    61→\n    62→**Issue B: Truncation penalty may be insufficient**\n    63→\n    64→Iteration 6 added a `-0.15` rawScore penalty to structural headings whose significant words are proper suffixes of another structural heading's words (`FRON` ← `SAFFRON`). This was designed to demote `FRON WHEAT BUNS (VARIATION 1)` below the threshold.\n    65→\n    66→However, the penalty is a fixed value and may not be sufficient depending on embedding scores. If `FRON WHEAT BUNS (VARIATION 1)` has a high rawScore (e.g. 0.40), after penalty it becomes 0.25. Its thresholdScore = 0.33. If the correct join (`SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK / COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D)`) scores lower (e.g. 0.38), its bestThresholdScore = 0.46, threshold = 0.322. In this scenario, FRON's thresholdScore 0.33 still exceeds threshold 0.322 — FRON survives.\n    67→\n    68→If FRON and the correct join both survive, the multi-title guard keeps both (two ALL_CAPS candidates). Output becomes `FRON WHEAT BUNS (VARIATION 1) + SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK / COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D)` — wrong on two counts.\n    69→\n    70→**Root cause (primary):** The OCR text has `/` but the expected title has `:` (a filesystem substitution artifact). Any algorithm output from this text will contain `/`, never matching the expected `:` substring.\n    71→\n    72→**Root cause (secondary):** The fixed `-0.15` truncation penalty may not reliably demote garbled structural headings across varying embedding score distributions.\n    73→\n    74→---\n    75→\n    76→## Common Themes\n    77→\n    78→### Theme 1: Suffix fragments survive and kill correct joins via dedup (case 1)\n    79→\n    80→The continuation protection (iteration 6) only removes the *prefix* single (`Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce`) when the join survives. It does not remove the *suffix* single (`& Coriander`). The dedup \"shorter wins\" rule then removes the join because `& coriander` is a substring of it and shorter. Fixing the prefix-side while ignoring the suffix-side is incomplete.\n    81→\n    82→### Theme 2: OCR-to-filename character substitution causes evaluation mismatch (case 2)\n    83→\n    84→The file naming convention encodes `:` in place of `/` (since `/` is illegal in filenames). When the OCR text uses `/` as a structural separator, the algorithm's output will always differ from the expected title by one character. This is a data/evaluation issue, not an algorithm issue. The algorithm may actually be extracting the correct structural heading from the OCR text but failing the match because of this encoding mismatch.\n    85→\n    86→To fix: either normalize `/` ↔ `:` in `titles_match`, or rename the input file with `÷` or another character, or treat `/` and `:` as equivalent separators when comparing.\n    87→\n    88→### Theme 3: Fixed-value penalties on embedding scores are fragile (case 2)\n    89→\n    90→The `-0.15` truncation penalty is an empirically chosen constant applied to a floating-point embedding score. Because embedding scores vary across texts, a fixed penalty can eliminate the garbled candidate in some cases but fail in others. A more robust approach would be relative penalization, disqualification (set rawScore to a large negative), or using a rule-based pre-filter to block clearly garbled structural headings before the scoring phase.\n    91→\n    92→### Theme 4: \"Shorter wins\" dedup interacts badly with split titles (cases 1 and 2, persistent)\n    93→\n    94→The dedup rule (keep shorter) is correct for ingredient run-ons but wrong for multi-line titles where both halves of the title independently pass hard filters and threshold. The continuation protection added in iteration 6 addresses one direction (prefix removal) but not both directions. The suffix fragment can still trigger the \"shorter wins\" rule against the correct join.\n    95→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01UvcEb9Ss8NfNqSXXHwGaZ1","session_id":"f1cce918-fde6-46b5-9093-50476190ee9c","uuid":"54f31752-dfd7-46af-aef4-6fa1729a20d6"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01PCMSqpAE8EiWhBSJGySYPN","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Improvement Plan — Iteration 7\n     2→\n     3→## Summary\n     4→\n     5→Two failures remain at 66.7% accuracy. One is a genuine algorithm gap (suffix fragment survival in dedup), the other is primarily an evaluation harness bug (filesystem character substitution). Both are fixable with targeted, low-risk changes.\n     6→\n     7→---\n     8→\n     9→## Root Cause Analysis\n    10→\n    11→### Failure 1: `Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce & Coriander` → no match\n    12→\n    13→**Input structure:**\n    14→```\n    15→Line 1: Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce\n    16→Line 2: & Coriander\n    17→Line 3: [body text, >80 chars, filtered]\n    18→```\n    19→\n    20→**What happens now:**\n    21→\n    22→1. `buildCandidates` generates three relevant candidates:\n    23→   - `\"Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce\"` (single, origin: \"single\")\n    24→   - `\"& Coriander\"` (single, origin: \"single\")\n    25→   - `\"Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce & Coriander\"` (origin: \"2-line\")\n    26→\n    27→2. The iteration 6 `survivingJoins` block (lines 394–406) correctly removes the **prefix** single `\"Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce\"` because the join starts with it and the remainder (`& Coriander`) begins with `&` — a continuation character.\n    28→\n    29→3. But `\"& Coriander\"` itself remains as a standalone candidate. It passes all hard filters: 11 chars, no measurement, starts with `&` (not lowercase), two words.\n    30→\n    31→4. The dedup filter (lines 413–421) sees that `\"& coriander\"` is a substring of the join AND shorter → the join is removed.\n    32→\n    33→5. Only `\"& Coriander\"` survives (or nothing, if it falls below threshold). Either way, no match.\n    34→\n    35→**Root cause:** The continuation protection is one-directional — it removes the prefix half of a split title but not the suffix half. The suffix fragment then triggers the \"shorter wins\" dedup rule against the complete join, destroying it.\n    36→\n    37→### Failure 2: `SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK : COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D)` → no match\n    38→\n    39→**Input structure:**\n    40→```\n    41→Line 29: FRON WHEAT BUNS (VARIATION 1)     ← garbled OCR from previous recipe\n    42→Line 54: SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK     ← correct title line 1\n    43→Line 55: / COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D)    ← correct title line 2\n    44→```\n    45→\n    46→**What happens now:**\n    47→\n    48→The iteration 6 changes (embedding-based `baseHeading` selection, truncation penalty, continuation extension, `survivingJoins` protection) likely produce the correct output: `SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK / COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D)`.\n    49→\n    50→**But it still fails the evaluation** because of a character mismatch:\n    51→\n    52→- The expected title (from the filename) uses `:` → `SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK : COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D)`\n    53→- The OCR text uses `/` → `SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK / COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D)`\n    54→- The `/` in the original cookbook text was substituted with `:` in the filename because `/` is illegal in filesystem paths.\n    55→\n    56→The `titles_match` function in `title-loop.py` performs exact normalized substring matching:\n    57→```python\n    58→extracted_norm = normalize(extracted)\n    59→expected_parts = [normalize(p) for p in expected.split(\"+\")]\n    60→return all(part in extracted_norm for part in expected_parts)\n    61→```\n    62→\n    63→`\"saffron wheat buns with quark : cottage cheese (variation d)\"` is not contained in `\"saffron wheat buns with quark / cottage cheese (variation d)\"`. The single-character difference (`:` vs `/`) causes the match to fail.\n    64→\n    65→**Root cause (primary):** The evaluation harness does not account for the filesystem character substitution. This is a data/evaluation bug, not an algorithm bug. The algorithm is likely already producing the correct output from the OCR text.\n    66→\n    67→**Root cause (secondary):** The fixed `-0.15` truncation penalty for `FRON WHEAT BUNS (VARIATION 1)` is fragile. While the embedding-quality `baseHeading` selection (iteration 6) should prefer the correct title, a hard disqualification would be more robust than a soft penalty.\n    68→\n    69→---\n    70→\n    71→## Proposed Changes\n    72→\n    73→### Change 1: Remove suffix fragments from surviving continuation joins (fixes Failure 1)\n    74→\n    75→**What:** Extend the `survivingJoins` block (lines 394–406) to also remove standalone candidates that are the **suffix** part of a surviving continuation join, not just the prefix part.\n    76→\n    77→**Where:** `lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts`, lines 394–406 — add a second filter pass within the same block.\n    78→\n    79→**Current code (lines 394–406):**\n    80→```ts\n    81→const survivingJoins = selected.filter((s) => s.origin === \"2-line\" || s.origin === \"3-line\");\n    82→if (survivingJoins.length > 0) {\n    83→  selected = selected.filter((s) => {\n    84→    if (s.origin !== \"single\") return true;\n    85→    const sLower = s.text.toLowerCase();\n    86→    return !survivingJoins.some((j) => {\n    87→      const jLower = j.text.toLowerCase();\n    88→      if (!jLower.startsWith(sLower + \" \")) return false;\n    89→      const remainder = jLower.slice(sLower.length + 1);\n    90→      return /^[/&+:(]/.test(remainder);\n    91→    });\n    92→  });\n    93→}\n    94→```\n    95→\n    96→**After:**\n    97→```ts\n    98→const survivingJoins = selected.filter((s) => s.origin === \"2-line\" || s.origin === \"3-line\");\n    99→if (survivingJoins.length > 0) {\n   100→  selected = selected.filter((s) => {\n   101→    if (s.origin !== \"single\") return true;\n   102→    const sLower = s.text.toLowerCase();\n   103→    // Remove PREFIX singles: \"Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce\" when\n   104→    // \"Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce & Coriander\" survived\n   105→    const isPrefixOfJoin = survivingJoins.some((j) => {\n   106→      const jLower = j.text.toLowerCase();\n   107→      if (!jLower.startsWith(sLower + \" \")) return false;\n   108→      const remainder = jLower.slice(sLower.length + 1);\n   109→      return /^[/&+:(]/.test(remainder);\n   110→    });\n   111→    if (isPrefixOfJoin) return false;\n   112→    // Remove SUFFIX singles: \"& Coriander\" when\n   113→    // \"Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce & Coriander\" survived\n   114→    const isSuffixOfJoin = survivingJoins.some((j) => {\n   115→      const jLower = j.text.toLowerCase();\n   116→      if (!jLower.endsWith(\" \" + sLower)) return false;\n   117→      // Only remove if the suffix starts with a continuation character\n   118→      return /^[/&+:(]/.test(sLower);\n   119→    });\n   120→    if (isSuffixOfJoin) return false;\n   121→    return true;\n   122→  });\n   123→}\n   124→```\n   125→\n   126→**Why this works for Failure 1:**\n   127→\n   128→- `\"& Coriander\"` is the suffix of the join `\"Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce & Coriander\"`.\n   129→- `\"& coriander\"` starts with `&` — a continuation character.\n   130→- The suffix is removed before dedup runs.\n   131→- The join survives dedup intact → correct title returned.\n   132→\n   133→**Why safe for existing tests:**\n   134→\n   135→- **Pierogi Ruskie:** The join `\"Pierogi Ruskie 200g mąki 3 ziemniaki\"` doesn't survive threshold (ingredient text scores low), so `survivingJoins` is empty or doesn't contain it. Even if it did, `\"200g mąki 3 ziemniaki\"` doesn't start with a continuation character.\n   136→- **ARAYES SHRAK:** `\"SHRAK\"` alone is 1 word, 5 chars. It may or may not pass hard filters, but even if it does, `\"shrak\"` does not start with `/&+:(`. Safe.\n   137→- **TITLE FIRST PART / SECOND PART:** `\"/ SECOND PART\"` starts with `/` and IS the suffix of the join. It would be removed. This is correct — we want the full join, not the fragment.\n   138→\n   139→**Regression risk:** Very low. The suffix removal only fires when (a) a continuation join survived the threshold, AND (b) the single candidate starts with a continuation character. This is an extremely narrow condition that matches exactly the split-title-with-continuation pattern.\n   140→\n   141→---\n   142→\n   143→### Change 2: Normalize `/` ↔ `:` in `titles_match` (fixes Failure 2 — primary)\n   144→\n   145→**What:** In the evaluation harness (`title-loop.py`), normalize `/` and `:` to a common character before comparing. This accounts for the filesystem character substitution where `:` replaces `/` in filenames.\n   146→\n   147→**Where:** `tools/title-loop/title-loop.py`, `titles_match` function (line 117).\n   148→\n   149→**Current code:**\n   150→```python\n   151→def titles_match(extracted: str, expected: str) -> bool:\n   152→    if not extracted:\n   153→        return False\n   154→    extracted_norm = normalize(extracted)\n   155→    expected_parts = [normalize(p) for p in expected.split(\"+\")]\n   156→    return all(part in extracted_norm for part in expected_parts)\n   157→```\n   158→\n   159→**After:**\n   160→```python\n   161→def normalize_separators(s: str) -> str:\n   162→    \"\"\"Normalize filesystem-substituted characters (: replaces / in filenames).\"\"\"\n   163→    return s.replace(\":\", \"/\")\n   164→\n   165→def titles_match(extracted: str, expected: str) -> bool:\n   166→    if not extracted:\n   167→        return False\n   168→    extracted_norm = normalize_separators(normalize(extracted))\n   169→    expected_parts = [normalize_separators(normalize(p)) for p in expected.split(\"+\")]\n   170→    return all(part in extracted_norm for part in expected_parts)\n   171→```\n   172→\n   173→**Why this works:** The expected title `\"saffron wheat buns with quark : cottage cheese (variation d)\"` becomes `\"saffron wheat buns with quark / cottage cheese (variation d)\"` after normalization. The extracted title `\"saffron wheat buns with quark / cottage cheese (variation d)\"` also normalizes to the same. Match succeeds.\n   174→\n   175→**Why safe:** The `:` → `/` normalization only affects comparison, not the algorithm output. No other test cases use `:` in expected titles. The `+` split in `expected.split(\"+\")` happens before separator normalization, so multi-title pages like `FINNISH MILK FLATBREADS + FINNISH POTATO FLATBREADS` are unaffected.\n   176→\n   177→**Note:** This change is in the evaluation harness (`tools/title-loop/title-loop.py`), not in `lib/text-classifier/`. It's the correct fix because the algorithm should output what the OCR says (`/`), and the evaluation should account for the filesystem encoding (`:`).\n   178→\n   179→---\n   180→\n   181→### Change 3: Hard disqualification for truncated OCR structural headings (defense-in-depth for Failure 2)\n   182→\n   183→**What:** Instead of a soft `-0.15` penalty, set the rawScore of a truncated structural heading to `-1.0` (effectively disqualifying it). This ensures that `FRON WHEAT BUNS (VARIATION 1)` can never win over `SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK` regardless of embedding score distributions.\n   184→\n   185→**Where:** `lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts`, lines 298–311 — the truncation penalty block.\n   186→\n   187→**Current code:**\n   188→```ts\n   189→if (hasTruncation) {\n   190→  sc.rawScore -= 0.15;\n   191→  break;\n   192→}\n   193→```\n   194→\n   195→**After:**\n   196→```ts\n   197→if (hasTruncation) {\n   198→  sc.rawScore = -1.0;  // Hard disqualification — truncated OCR artifact\n   199→  break;\n   200→}\n   201→```\n   202→\n   203→**Why this works:** The embedding-quality `baseHeading` selection already prefers the correct title in most cases. But if MiniLM embeddings ever produce a score distribution where the garbled fragment still wins after -0.15, the hard disqualification ensures it's eliminated. `-1.0` is so far below any plausible score that the truncated heading can never become `baseHeading` or pass the threshold.\n   204→\n   205→**Why safe:** The truncation detection (suffix match between significant words of two structural headings) is extremely precise. It only fires when one ALL_CAPS heading has a word that is a strict suffix of a word in another ALL_CAPS heading (e.g., `FRON` suffix of `SAFFRON`). This condition is nearly impossible to produce accidentally in real recipe titles. On the Finnish Flatbreads page, `FLATBREADS` appears in both but `ow !== w` and the suffix check prevents self-matching — neither word is a suffix of the other.\n   206→\n   207→---\n   208→\n   209→## Expected Impact\n   210→\n   211→| Change | Fixes | Risk | Scope |\n   212→|---|---|---|---|\n   213→| 1. Remove suffix fragments | Failure 1 (Baked Eggs) | Very low — narrow continuation-char guard | `title-extractor.ts` lines 394–406 |\n   214→| 2. Normalize separators in `titles_match` | Failure 2 primary (evaluation mismatch) | None — comparison-only change | `title-loop.py` line 117 |\n   215→| 3. Hard disqualification for truncated headings | Failure 2 defense-in-depth | Very low — strict cross-match only | `title-extractor.ts` lines 306–308 |\n   216→\n   217→### Expected Accuracy\n   218→\n   219→- **Failure 1 (Baked Eggs):** Fixed by Change 1. The suffix `\"& Coriander\"` is removed before dedup → join `\"Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce & Coriander\"` survives → match.\n   220→- **Failure 2 (Saffron Wheat Buns):** Fixed by Change 2. The algorithm already outputs `\"SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK / COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D)\"` from the OCR. With separator normalization, `titles_match` recognizes it as matching the expected `\":\"` variant. Change 3 adds insurance.\n   221→- **All passing tests:** Unaffected. Changes 1 and 3 have narrow guards. Change 2 only affects the harness comparison.\n   222→- **Projected accuracy:** 8/8 = 100% on real files (up from 6/8 = 66.7%).\n   223→\n   224→### Regression Risks\n   225→\n   226→- **Pierogi Ruskie:** Change 1 does NOT remove any fragments for this case (no continuation characters in the ingredient suffix). Dedup correctly keeps the shorter form.\n   227→- **ARAYES SHRAK:** `\"SHRAK\"` doesn't start with a continuation character. The existing prefix removal handles ARAYES. No change in behavior.\n   228→- **FINNISH MILK FLATBREADS + FINNISH POTATO FLATBREADS:** No truncation relationship between the two titles. No separator normalization needed. Unaffected.\n   229→- **MIXED SEED CRISPBREAD, OVERNIGHT STRAIGHT PIZZA DOUGH:** Single-title pages with no split titles or truncation. Unaffected.\n   230→\n   231→### Key Insight\n   232→\n   233→This iteration's changes are small and targeted because the iteration 6 improvements (embedding-quality baseHeading, thresholdScore, continuation protection) were fundamentally sound. The remaining failures are:\n   234→1. An incomplete edge in the continuation protection (prefix but not suffix removal) — a one-sided fix for a two-sided problem.\n   235→2. An evaluation harness bug where filesystem character encoding creates a false negative.\n   236→\n   237→Neither indicates a fundamental design flaw. The algorithm is working correctly for the Saffron case — it just can't get credit for it due to the evaluation mismatch.\n   238→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01UvcEb9Ss8NfNqSXXHwGaZ1","session_id":"f1cce918-fde6-46b5-9093-50476190ee9c","uuid":"94359e9f-2931-4593-a242-eaaf3c9b8d56"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_018SciqZufX1ZmoQntXwBVmE","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Title Extraction Failures — Iteration 7 Analysis\n     2→\n     3→## Failure 1: Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce & Coriander\n     4→\n     5→**Input structure:**\n     6→```\n     7→Line 1: \"Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce\"\n     8→Line 2: \"& Coriander\"\n     9→Line 3: (long body paragraph)\n    10→Line 4: \"SERVES *\"\n    11→```\n    12→\n    13→**Why it fails:**\n    14→\n    15→The title is split across two lines with a continuation character (\"&\") on the second line. The 2-line join \"Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce & Coriander\" (54 chars) is a valid candidate and passes `passesHardFilters`. However, the 2-line join's embedding score is likely lower than the single-line prefix because embedding models tend to score the semantically complete-looking fragment (\"Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce\") more confidently as a recipe title than the joined string (which includes the dangling \"& Coriander\" fragment).\n    16→\n    17→If the join is below the threshold while the single-line prefix is above it, then `survivingJoins` is empty after threshold filtering. This means the continuation-prefix-protection logic does **not** fire. The single \"Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce\" survives as the only candidate. The dedup step would also eliminate the join if it somehow survived (it's a superstring of the single, and \"shorter wins\"). Result: the truncated prefix is returned, missing \"& Coriander\".\n    18→\n    19→Additionally, \"& Coriander\" itself passes `passesHardFilters` as a standalone candidate (it doesn't start lowercase, has sufficient vowel ratio, and isn't caught by `hasGarbledWord`). This introduces noise in the candidate pool.\n    20→\n    21→---\n    22→\n    23→## Failure 2: CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM\n    24→\n    25→**Input structure:**\n    26→```\n    27→Line 1: \"Lato | Dania główne\"      ← category header (Polish: \"Summer | Main courses\")\n    28→Line 2: \"CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM\"  ← recipe title\n    29→Line 3: \"WARZYWA I BOCZEK\"         ← section sub-header within recipe\n    30→```\n    31→\n    32→**Why it fails:**\n    33→\n    34→Both \"CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM\" and \"WARZYWA I BOCZEK\" pass `isStructuralHeading`:\n    35→\n    36→- \"CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM\": sigWords = [\"CHLEBEK\"(7), \"WARZYWAMI\"(9), \"BOCZKIEM\"(8)]. All ≥ 4. ✓\n    37→- \"WARZYWA I BOCZEK\": sigWords = [\"WARZYWA\"(7), \"BOCZEK\"(6)]; \"I\" filtered (1 letter). Both ≥ 4. ✓\n    38→\n    39→Both are ALL_CAPS and likely pass the embedding threshold (Polish food nouns embed well against the title reference). The multi-title guard at the end then detects `allCapsSelected.length >= 2` and returns **both**, producing \"CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM + WARZYWA I BOCZEK\" instead of just the recipe title.\n    40→\n    41→The algorithm cannot distinguish a sub-section header (\"WARZYWA I BOCZEK\" = \"Vegetables and Bacon\") that appears within the body of a single recipe from a second recipe title. Both look identical structurally.\n    42→\n    43→A further complication: the 2-line join \"CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM WARZYWA I BOCZEK\" also qualifies as a structural heading and may appear in candidates, compounding the multi-heading confusion.\n    44→\n    45→---\n    46→\n    47→## Failure 3: Faszerowana papryka\n    48→\n    49→**Input structure:**\n    50→```\n    51→Line 1: \"Faszerowana papryka\"     ← Polish title (\"Stuffed peppers\"), mixed case\n    52→Line 2: \"PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM\"    ← Korean dish name romanized, ALL_CAPS\n    53→Line 3: \"파프리카 계란찜\"          ← Korean script (isLikelyGarbled → no latin letters)\n    54→Line 4: \"Ten bardzo prosty...\"    ← body text, starts lowercase → filtered\n    55→```\n    56→\n    57→**Why it fails:**\n    58→\n    59→\"PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM\" qualifies as a structural heading:\n    60→- isAllCaps = true\n    61→- sigWords = [\"PAPRIKA\"(7), \"GYERANJJIM\"(10)]. Both ≥ 4. ✓\n    62→\n    63→It receives `allCapsBonus` (0.08) + `structuralBonus` (0.10) = **+0.18** total.\n    64→\n    65→\"Faszerowana papryka\" is a plain mixed-case line at position 0. It receives no bonuses. Even with the positional factor (`1.0 + 0.12 * 1.0 = 1.12` multiplier for position 0), this is unlikely to overcome +0.18 in additive bonuses on top of \"PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM\"'s own rawScore.\n    66→\n    67→The multi-title guard then sees exactly one ALL_CAPS candidate, collapses `selected` to the highest-scoring candidate, and returns \"PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM\".\n    68→\n    69→The algorithm misidentifies the Korean romanization (a subtitle/transliteration of the title) as the recipe title because it's ALL_CAPS. The actual Polish title, which appears first and is the canonical recipe name for this cookbook, is discarded.\n    70→\n    71→---\n    72→\n    73→## Failure 4: SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK : COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D)\n    74→\n    75→**Input structure:**\n    76→```\n    77→Lines 1–28:  Heavily garbled OCR text (previous recipe page bleeds, partial words)\n    78→Line 29:     \"FRON WHEAT BUNS (VARIATION 1)\"  ← truncated OCR of prior recipe heading\n    79→...\n    80→Line 54:     \"SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK\"\n    81→Line 55:     \"/ COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D)\"\n    82→```\n    83→\n    84→**Why it fails (two independent issues):**\n    85→\n    86→**Issue A — OCR character mismatch:**\n    87→The expected output uses `\":\"` as separator (\"QUARK : COTTAGE CHEESE\"), but the OCR text on line 55 reads `\"/ COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D)\"` with a slash. The algorithm can only produce text present in the input. Even if the continuation join logic works correctly, the best possible output from this OCR text is \"SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK / COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D)\", which does not match the expected ground truth. The \"/\" in the OCR is a misread colon from the original print.\n    88→\n    89→**Issue B — Candidate pre-filter may exclude the 2-line join:**\n    90→The top-25 pre-filter in `buildCandidates` sorts candidates by ALL_CAPS first, then by word count ≤ 5. The single \"SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK\" (5 words, ALL_CAPS) scores higher priority than the 2-line join \"SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK / COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D)\" (9 words, ALL_CAPS). If the total candidate count exceeds 25 (likely given ~45 non-empty lines after the garbled burst), the longer join may be cut. If the join is absent from `rawScored`, the `firstStructuralHeading` continuation logic falls back to `baseHeading` (the single), returning the incomplete title.\n    91→\n    92→The truncation-detection penalty for \"FRON WHEAT BUNS (VARIATION 1)\" → \"SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK\" is correctly implemented and should work. That is not the cause of failure here.\n    93→\n    94→---\n    95→\n    96→## Common Themes\n    97→\n    98→### 1. Continuation joins are fragile\n    99→Cases 1 and 4 both involve a title split across two lines where the continuation line starts with a symbol (\"&\", \"/\"). The continuation-protection logic is conditional on the join surviving the threshold (case 1) and on the join being present in the candidate pool at all (case 4). These preconditions silently fail, and the algorithm returns the first half of the title with no indication that anything is wrong.\n   100→\n   101→### 2. Intra-recipe ALL_CAPS section headers defeat the multi-title guard\n   102→Case 2 shows that the multi-title guard (`allCapsSelected.length >= 2 → return all`) cannot distinguish a recipe's sub-section heading from a second recipe title on a multi-recipe page. In single-recipe layouts, ALL_CAPS headers like \"WARZYWA I BOCZEK\" (ingredients section) or \"PRZYGOTOWANIE\" (preparation) trigger the same structural heading logic as recipe titles.\n   103→\n   104→### 3. ALL_CAPS bonuses override document position for bilingual pages\n   105→Case 3 demonstrates that the structural (+0.10) and ALL_CAPS (+0.08) bonuses are large enough to override a first-position mixed-case title when an ALL_CAPS subtitle/romanization appears on line 2. The algorithm has no mechanism to prefer a mixed-case title on line 1 over an ALL_CAPS romanization on line 2 when only one ALL_CAPS candidate survives threshold.\n   106→\n   107→### 4. Ground truth / OCR separator mismatch\n   108→Case 4 reveals a category of failure where the OCR misreads a character (colon → slash) such that the correct string is not present anywhere in the input. No algorithmic change can fix this — it requires either correcting the expected value or normalising separators post-extraction.\n   109→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01UvcEb9Ss8NfNqSXXHwGaZ1","session_id":"f1cce918-fde6-46b5-9093-50476190ee9c","uuid":"087dc9f2-6269-4d8d-b7e5-695a58d40001"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01BBUspDZneuNZomGRSrmH1X","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Iteration 8 Failure Analysis\n     2→\n     3→## Failures\n     4→\n     5→### 1. `Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce & Coriander` → `''`\n     6→\n     7→**Input structure:**\n     8→```\n     9→Line 1: \"Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce\"\n    10→Line 2: \"& Coriander\"\n    11→Line 3: (long body text paragraph)\n    12→...\n    13→Lines 4+: ingredients starting with numbers, long body text\n    14→```\n    15→\n    16→**What the algorithm does:**\n    17→The pre-merge step in `buildCandidates` correctly identifies \"& Coriander\" as a continuation line (starts with `&`) and merges it with the preceding line, producing the single candidate \"Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce & Coriander\". This candidate passes all hard filters: 54 chars (under 80), no measurement patterns, no metadata pattern, not garbled.\n    18→\n    19→**Why it fails — embedding scoring:**\n    20→The merged title contains ingredient-like terms (\"Harissa Tomato Sauce\", \"Feta\") that increase cosine similarity to `HEADER_REFERENCE` (\"ingredients list, cooking directions, section heading\"). If `headerSim >= titleSim`, then `rawScore = titleSim - max(headerSim, noiseSim) <= 0`. With no `allCapsBonus` (mixed-case) and no `structuralBonus` (not structural heading), the final score `rawScore * 1.12` can fall below the 0.08 minimum threshold. The candidate is filtered out, and `selected` becomes empty, returning `undefined`/`''`.\n    21→\n    22→The code even comments on line 413: \"the pre-merge step above already handles the common Baked Eggs case\" — yet the candidate is silently discarded in scoring. The hard filters pass but the threshold gate fails.\n    23→\n    24→**Root cause:** Descriptive recipe titles containing ingredient names (sauces, cheeses, spices) are penalised by the HEADER_REFERENCE because ingredient words pull the embedding toward the ingredient-list reference rather than the title reference. There is no floor or fallback for a candidate that passes all hard filters and is the only candidate in the pool.\n    25→\n    26→---\n    27→\n    28→### 2. `Faszerowana papryka` → `'PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM'`\n    29→\n    30→**Input structure:**\n    31→```\n    32→Line 1: \"Faszerowana papryka\"   (Polish title)\n    33→Line 2: \"PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM\"  (ALL_CAPS Korean-romanised subtitle)\n    34→Line 3: \"파프리카 계란찜\"           (Korean script — filtered by isLikelyGarbled: letters.length < 2)\n    35→Line 4: (Polish body text, starts lowercase → filtered)\n    36→```\n    37→\n    38→**What the algorithm does:**\n    39→Both \"Faszerowana papryka\" and \"PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM\" pass hard filters:\n    40→- \"Faszerowana papryka\": 19 chars, starts uppercase, Polish vowel ratio ~0.44, no measurements. Passes.\n    41→- \"PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM\": ALL_CAPS, `isStructuralHeading` qualifies it (≥2 sig words, each ≥4 alpha chars).\n    42→\n    43→In scoring, \"PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM\" receives `+0.08` allCapsBonus + `+0.10` structuralBonus = `+0.18` on top of its rawScore. \"Faszerowana papryka\" receives neither bonus.\n    44→\n    45→**Why the first-line protection fails:**\n    46→The algorithm has an explicit guard (lines 468–479) for exactly this pattern: \"mixed-case title at position 0 followed by a single ALL_CAPS subtitle\". The guard correctly identifies `pos0 = selected.find(s => s.position === 0 && !isAllCaps(s.text))` and `allCapsCandidates.length === 1` at position 1.\n    47→\n    48→But the guard has a precondition: both candidates must already be in `selected` (i.e., both must have passed the threshold filter). The protection fires *after* the threshold filter, not before it.\n    49→\n    50→If \"Faszerowana papryka\" scores below threshold — which is plausible because:\n    51→- TITLE_REFERENCE is English; a short Polish phrase has lower cosine similarity to it\n    52→- The threshold is inflated to `bestThresholdScore * 0.7` where `bestThresholdScore` comes from \"PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM\"'s strong score (+0.18 bonuses)\n    53→\n    54→...then \"Faszerowana papryka\" never enters `selected`, `pos0 = null`, and the protection is never triggered. The result is \"PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM\" alone.\n    55→\n    56→**Root cause:** The first-line protection has a self-defeating design: it only activates when the correct first-line title has *already* survived the threshold independently. When the ALL_CAPS candidate inflates the threshold (via its bonuses) to a level the mixed-case title can't reach, the protection becomes a no-op. The protection is needed most precisely when the mixed-case title is outscored — but that is also when it cannot fire.\n    57→\n    58→---\n    59→\n    60→## Common Themes\n    61→\n    62→### A. ALL_CAPS bias undermines correct mixed-case titles in bilingual recipes\n    63→The `+0.08` allCapsBonus and `+0.10` structuralBonus create a 0.18-point advantage for ALL_CAPS candidates. In bilingual cookbooks where the primary-language title is mixed-case and an ALL_CAPS romanisation or translation follows on the next line, this bonus systematically elevates the secondary subtitle over the actual title. The first-line protection was designed to compensate but fails when the all-caps advantage raises the threshold beyond the mixed-case title's reach.\n    64→\n    65→### B. The first-line protection is a post-hoc bandage that depends on the problem it's meant to solve\n    66→The guard on lines 468–479 requires both candidates to be in `selected` before it can act. Its precondition — `pos0.score >= threshold` — means it only fires when the mixed-case title didn't need the protection in the first place. When the mixed-case title is genuinely outscored by the ALL_CAPS candidate (the case the protection targets), the guard silently skips, making it ineffective.\n    67→\n    68→### C. Ingredient-bearing recipe titles are penalised by the HEADER_REFERENCE\n    69→Recipes named after their key components (e.g. \"Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce\") have titles that semantically overlap with ingredient-list vocabulary. The embedding scorer cannot distinguish \"this is the name of a dish that contains these ingredients\" from \"this is a fragment of an ingredient list\". The rawScore formula `titleSim - max(headerSim, noiseSim)` provides no floor for candidates that pass all structural filters, meaning a legitimate title with modest differentiation can fall below threshold entirely.\n    70→\n    71→### D. No fallback when the candidate pool is unambiguous\n    72→When there is exactly one candidate (or one dominant candidate that clearly passes all hard filters), the threshold mechanism can still discard it if the embedding similarity difference is too small. There is no \"if only one candidate exists and it passed all structural filters, return it\" safety net.\n    73→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01UvcEb9Ss8NfNqSXXHwGaZ1","session_id":"f1cce918-fde6-46b5-9093-50476190ee9c","uuid":"6336cfc7-4d90-4fd0-bd53-2bee39a59516"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_017ZEs1RGUEnBY9wvj6f5HPf","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Improvement Plan — Iteration 8\n     2→\n     3→## Executive Summary\n     4→\n     5→Three of the four failures share a common root cause: the algorithm treats structural signals (ALL_CAPS, continuation characters, document position) as secondary bonuses on top of embedding scores, when in fact these structural signals are often **more reliable** than embeddings for determining recipe titles. The fix is to promote structural signals from \"bonus modifiers\" to \"pipeline-shaping decisions\" that happen before embedding scoring.\n     6→\n     7→The fourth failure (SAFFRON/OCR mismatch) is an evaluation harness issue, not an algorithm issue.\n     8→\n     9→---\n    10→\n    11→## Change 1: Pre-merge continuation lines before candidate generation\n    12→\n    13→**Fixes:** Failure 1 (Baked Eggs), Failure 4B (SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS join excluded from top-25)\n    14→\n    15→### Root Cause\n    16→\n    17→Continuation joins are fragile because they depend on a long chain of conditions all being true simultaneously:\n    18→1. The 2-line join must pass `passesHardFilters` (80 char limit can exclude long joins)\n    19→2. The join must survive the top-25 pre-filter (longer word count deprioritized)\n    20→3. The join must score above the embedding threshold independently\n    21→4. The `survivingJoins` protection must fire (requires join in `selected`)\n    22→5. Dedup \"shorter wins\" must not kill the join\n    23→\n    24→If ANY of these fail, the algorithm silently returns the truncated first half. This has been the single most persistent failure pattern across all 7 iterations — every attempt to patch it downstream has introduced new edge cases.\n    25→\n    26→### Proposed Fix\n    27→\n    28→Move continuation merging **upstream**, into `buildCandidates`, before candidates are generated:\n    29→\n    30→```typescript\n    31→// NEW: Pre-merge continuation lines before candidate generation.\n    32→// A continuation line starts with /&+:( — it's never a standalone title.\n    33→const mergedLines: Array<{ text: string; index: number }> = [];\n    34→for (let i = 0; i < nonEmptyLines.length; i++) {\n    35→  const line = nonEmptyLines[i];\n    36→  // Check if the NEXT line starts with a continuation character\n    37→  if (i + 1 < nonEmptyLines.length) {\n    38→    const nextText = nonEmptyLines[i + 1].text;\n    39→    if (/^[/&+:(]/.test(nextText)) {\n    40→      // Merge next line into this one\n    41→      mergedLines.push({\n    42→        text: `${line.text} ${nextText}`,\n    43→        index: line.index,\n    44→      });\n    45→      i++; // Skip the continuation line\n    46→      continue;\n    47→    }\n    48→  }\n    49→  mergedLines.push(line);\n    50→}\n    51→```\n    52→\n    53→Then use `mergedLines` instead of `nonEmptyLines` for candidate generation.\n    54→\n    55→### Before / After\n    56→\n    57→**Before (Baked Eggs):**\n    58→- Candidate pool contains: `\"Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce\"` (single), `\"& Coriander\"` (single), and `\"Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce & Coriander\"` (2-line join)\n    59→- The join must independently survive threshold, pre-filter, and dedup\n    60→- `\"& Coriander\"` pollutes the candidate pool as a standalone candidate\n    61→- If the join's embedding score is lower than the single's, protection logic doesn't fire → returns truncated title\n    62→\n    63→**After (Baked Eggs):**\n    64→- Lines 1+2 pre-merged into `\"Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce & Coriander\"`\n    65→- Candidate pool contains this as a **single** candidate with `origin: \"single\"`\n    66→- `\"& Coriander\"` never enters the pool as standalone\n    67→- No dependence on join survival, threshold, or dedup — the merged line IS the candidate\n    68→- Result: `\"Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce & Coriander\"` ✓\n    69→\n    70→**Before (SAFFRON):**\n    71→- `\"SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK\"` (5 words, ALL_CAPS) and `\"/ COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D)\"` (single) enter pool separately\n    72→- The 2-line join `\"SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK / COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D)\"` (9 words) is deprioritized in the top-25 pre-filter (word count > 5)\n    73→- With ~45 non-empty lines after garbled burst, the join may be cut\n    74→\n    75→**After (SAFFRON):**\n    76→- Lines 54+55 pre-merged into `\"SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK / COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D)\"`\n    77→- Enters pool as a single candidate, not subject to join-specific deprioritization\n    78→- `\"/ COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D)\"` never enters pool as standalone\n    79→- Result: `\"SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK / COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D)\"` ✓\n    80→\n    81→### Impact on Existing Tests\n    82→\n    83→This change is **safe for existing passing tests**:\n    84→- ARAYES SHRAK: line 2 is `\"SHRAK\"` which does NOT start with `/&+:(` → no pre-merge, existing logic handles it\n    85→- FINNISH MILK FLATBREADS + FINNISH POTATO FLATBREADS: second title starts with `\"FINNISH\"`, not a continuation char → no pre-merge\n    86→- Pierogi Ruskie: no continuation lines → unchanged\n    87→- All other passing tests: no continuation lines\n    88→\n    89→### Cleanup\n    90→\n    91→With pre-merging in place, the downstream `survivingJoins` continuation protection block (lines ~390-418 in current code) becomes largely redundant for continuation-character joins. It can be simplified but should be kept for non-continuation 2-line joins (e.g., titles that happen to span two lines without a leading symbol).\n    92→\n    93→---\n    94→\n    95→## Change 2: Ingredient-gap detection in multi-title guard\n    96→\n    97→**Fixes:** Failure 2 (CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM)\n    98→\n    99→### Root Cause\n   100→\n   101→The multi-title guard at lines 441-448 uses a simple rule: if `allCapsSelected.length >= 2`, return all ALL_CAPS candidates joined with `+`. This cannot distinguish between:\n   102→- **Multi-recipe pages** (two independent recipe titles): FINNISH MILK FLATBREADS + FINNISH POTATO FLATBREADS\n   103→- **Single-recipe pages with section headers**: CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM (title) + WARZYWA I BOCZEK (ingredient section header)\n   104→\n   105→The input for CHLEBEK shows:\n   106→```\n   107→Line 2: CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM  ← title\n   108→Line 3: WARZYWA I BOCZEK                ← section header\n   109→Line 4: 500 g strączków zielonego groszku  ← ingredient (has measurement!)\n   110→Line 5: 1 żółta papryka                    ← ingredient (starts with number!)\n   111→...\n   112→Line 9: CHLEBEK                          ← another section header\n   113→Line 10: 500 g mąki                      ← ingredient\n   114→```\n   115→\n   116→Between and after the ALL_CAPS headings, there are ingredient lines with measurements and numbers. On a multi-recipe page (like FINNISH FLATBREADS), the second recipe title appears after the FIRST recipe's body text ends, typically after a page break or significant gap — NOT immediately followed by ingredients that clearly belong to the preceding heading.\n   117→\n   118→### Proposed Fix\n   119→\n   120→Add an ingredient-gap check to the multi-title guard. When `allCapsSelected.length >= 2`, examine the original lines between each pair of ALL_CAPS headings. If ingredient-like content (lines with measurements or starting with numbers) appears between them, they are section headers within the same recipe.\n   121→\n   122→```typescript\n   123→// Inside the multi-title guard, after finding allCapsSelected.length >= 2:\n   124→if (allCapsSelected.length >= 2) {\n   125→  // Check if ALL_CAPS headings are separated by ingredient-like content\n   126→  // (measurements, numbered items) — if so, they're section headers\n   127→  // within a single recipe, not separate recipe titles.\n   128→  const sortedCaps = [...allCapsSelected].sort((a, b) => a.position - b.position);\n   129→  const firstPos = sortedCaps[0].position;\n   130→  const lastPos = sortedCaps[sortedCaps.length - 1].position;\n   131→\n   132→  const linesBetween = lines.slice(firstPos + 1, lastPos);\n   133→  const hasIngredientsBetween = linesBetween.some(\n   134→    (l) => looksLikeIngredient(l.trim()) || /^\\s*\\d/.test(l.trim())\n   135→  );\n   136→\n   137→  if (hasIngredientsBetween) {\n   138→    // Same recipe — keep only the first (earliest position) ALL_CAPS heading\n   139→    selected = [sortedCaps[0]];\n   140→  } else {\n   141→    // Likely multi-recipe page — keep all\n   142→    selected = allCapsSelected;\n   143→  }\n   144→}\n   145→```\n   146→\n   147→### Before / After\n   148→\n   149→**Before (CHLEBEK):**\n   150→- `allCapsSelected` = [`\"CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM\"` (pos 1), `\"WARZYWA I BOCZEK\"` (pos 2)]\n   151→- Guard sees 2 ALL_CAPS → returns both joined: `\"CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM + WARZYWA I BOCZEK\"`\n   152→\n   153→**After (CHLEBEK):**\n   154→- Same `allCapsSelected`, but now checks lines between positions 1 and 2\n   155→- Line 3 (`\"500 g strączków...\"`) contains measurement \"g\" → `hasIngredientsBetween = true`\n   156→- Guard keeps only first: `\"CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM\"` ✓\n   157→\n   158→**Safety for FINNISH FLATBREADS:**\n   159→- Two ALL_CAPS headings: `\"FINNISH MILK FLATBREADS\"` and `\"FINNISH POTATO FLATBREADS\"`\n   160→- Lines between them are recipe body text (instructions), NOT ingredients with measurements\n   161→- Actually — need to verify this. The FINNISH FLATBREADS test case has recipe text between the two titles which likely includes ingredients.\n   162→\n   163→### Risk Mitigation\n   164→\n   165→The ingredient-gap heuristic could be too aggressive if the FINNISH FLATBREADS page has ingredient lines between the two titles. To handle this, refine the check: require that **most** lines between headings (>50%) are ingredient-like, not just one. A multi-recipe page may have a few ingredient lines at the end of recipe 1, but the majority of lines between two recipe titles will be body text/instructions.\n   166→\n   167→Alternative refinement: check if ingredient lines appear **immediately after** the first heading (within the next 3 lines). Section headers in single-recipe layouts are typically followed directly by ingredients. Multi-recipe titles are followed by body text or instructions first.\n   168→\n   169→```typescript\n   170→// Refined: check if ingredients appear in the first 3 lines after the first heading\n   171→const immediateLines = lines.slice(firstPos + 1, Math.min(firstPos + 4, lastPos));\n   172→const hasImmediateIngredients = immediateLines.some(\n   173→  (l) => looksLikeIngredient(l.trim()) || /^\\s*\\d/.test(l.trim())\n   174→);\n   175→```\n   176→\n   177→For CHLEBEK: line immediately after the first heading is \"WARZYWA I BOCZEK\" (another heading), and the line after THAT is `\"500 g strączków...\"` (ingredient). So we need to look past intermediate headings. Better approach: check if ANY heading other than the first is immediately followed by ingredient lines.\n   178→\n   179→```typescript\n   180→// Check if any non-first ALL_CAPS heading is followed by ingredient content\n   181→// within 2 lines — this marks it as a section header, not a recipe title\n   182→const isSubHeader = sortedCaps.slice(1).every((cap) => {\n   183→  const nextLines = lines.slice(cap.position + 1, cap.position + 3);\n   184→  return nextLines.some(\n   185→    (l) => looksLikeIngredient(l.trim()) || /^\\s*\\d/.test(l.trim())\n   186→  );\n   187→});\n   188→\n   189→if (isSubHeader) {\n   190→  selected = [sortedCaps[0]];\n   191→} else {\n   192→  selected = allCapsSelected;\n   193→}\n   194→```\n   195→\n   196→This is more precise: it checks whether the **later** ALL_CAPS headings act like section headers (followed by ingredients) rather than recipe titles (followed by body text).\n   197→\n   198→### Expected Impact\n   199→\n   200→Fixes CHLEBEK without regressing FINNISH FLATBREADS, because the second FINNISH title is followed by its own recipe body text (instructions), not directly by ingredient lines.\n   201→\n   202→---\n   203→\n   204→## Change 3: First-line mixed-case title protection\n   205→\n   206→**Fixes:** Failure 3 (Faszerowana papryka)\n   207→\n   208→### Root Cause\n   209→\n   210→The scoring arithmetic makes it nearly impossible for a mixed-case line at position 0 to beat an ALL_CAPS line at position 1:\n   211→\n   212→| Candidate | rawScore (est.) | Position factor | ALL_CAPS bonus | Structural bonus | Final score |\n   213→|-----------|----------------|-----------------|----------------|-----------------|-------------|\n   214→| \"Faszerowana papryka\" (pos 0) | ~0.15 | ×1.12 | 0 | 0 | ~0.168 |\n   215→| \"PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM\" (pos 1) | ~0.12 | ×1.11 | +0.08 | +0.10 | ~0.313 |\n   216→\n   217→The ALL_CAPS bonuses (+0.18 combined) are designed for recipe books that use ALL_CAPS exclusively for titles. But bilingual cookbooks use mixed case for the primary language title and ALL_CAPS for the romanization/transliteration.\n   218→\n   219→The position-0 candidate is almost always the recipe title in every cookbook format observed. When a mixed-case candidate at position 0 has a reasonable embedding score, it should not lose to a position-1 ALL_CAPS candidate purely due to formatting bonuses.\n   220→\n   221→### Proposed Fix\n   222→\n   223→Add a **first-line title protection** rule after scoring, before the multi-title guard. When:\n   224→1. There is a mixed-case candidate at position 0 (or within the first 2 non-empty lines)\n   225→2. It passes the embedding threshold\n   226→3. The highest-scoring candidate is an ALL_CAPS line at position 1 (immediately following)\n   227→4. No other ALL_CAPS candidates exist further down\n   228→\n   229→Then: prefer the position-0 candidate, treating the ALL_CAPS line as a subtitle.\n   230→\n   231→```typescript\n   232→// First-line mixed-case title protection:\n   233→// If a mixed-case line at position 0 passes threshold and the only ALL_CAPS\n   234→// candidate is at position 1 (immediately following), the ALL_CAPS line is\n   235→// likely a subtitle/transliteration — prefer the first-line title.\n   236→if (selected.length >= 1) {\n   237→  const pos0 = selected.find(\n   238→    (s) => s.position === 0 && !isAllCaps(s.text)\n   239→  );\n   240→  const allCapsCandidates = selected.filter((s) => isAllCaps(s.text));\n   241→\n   242→  if (\n   243→    pos0 &&\n   244→    allCapsCandidates.length === 1 &&\n   245→    allCapsCandidates[0].position <= 2 && // immediately after title\n   246→    pos0.score >= threshold // has reasonable embedding score\n   247→  ) {\n   248→    // The ALL_CAPS line is a subtitle — remove it, keep position-0 title\n   249→    selected = selected.filter((s) => s !== allCapsCandidates[0]);\n   250→  }\n   251→}\n   252→```\n   253→\n   254→### Before / After\n   255→\n   256→**Before (Faszerowana papryka):**\n   257→- `selected` after threshold: both candidates survive\n   258→- Multi-title guard: 1 ALL_CAPS → collapse to highest score → `\"PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM\"` wins\n   259→- Result: `\"PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM\"` ✗\n   260→\n   261→**After (Faszerowana papryka):**\n   262→- First-line protection fires: pos0 = `\"Faszerowana papryka\"`, single ALL_CAPS at pos 1\n   263→- ALL_CAPS candidate removed as subtitle\n   264→- Result: `\"Faszerowana papryka\"` ✓\n   265→\n   266→### Safety for Other Tests\n   267→\n   268→- **MIXED SEED CRISPBREAD** (ALL_CAPS, single title, pos 0): pos0 IS all-caps → protection doesn't fire ✓\n   269→- **OVERNIGHT STRAIGHT PIZZA DOUGH** (ALL_CAPS, single title): same as above ✓\n   270→- **ARAYES SHRAK** (ALL_CAPS multi-word join): no mixed-case at pos 0 → doesn't fire ✓\n   271→- **FINNISH FLATBREADS** (two ALL_CAPS titles): `allCapsCandidates.length >= 2` → doesn't fire ✓\n   272→- **CHLEBEK** (ALL_CAPS title at pos 1, mixed-case category at pos 0): the category line `\"Lato | Dania główne\"` — need to check if this passes hard filters. It contains `\"|\"` and is a category header. `isLikelyGarbled` should catch this... let me check: it doesn't start lowercase, has valid vowel ratio, no garbled words. It would pass `passesHardFilters`. BUT: its embedding score as a recipe title should be very low (it's a category, not a dish name), so it likely won't pass the embedding threshold. If it does somehow pass: the protection would fire (mixed-case at pos 0, one ALL_CAPS at pos 1), incorrectly removing the real title.\n   273→\n   274→### Risk Mitigation for CHLEBEK Edge Case\n   275→\n   276→Add a guard: the position-0 mixed-case candidate must have a **minimum embedding rawScore** to qualify for protection. A category header like \"Lato | Dania główne\" will have a very low `rawScore` because it's not semantically similar to \"recipe name, dish title\". Set the minimum at the threshold value or at a fixed floor (e.g., rawScore ≥ 0.05).\n   277→\n   278→```typescript\n   279→// Additional guard: pos0 must have meaningful title similarity\n   280→const pos0Scored = scored.find(\n   281→  (s) => s.position === pos0.position && s.text === pos0.text\n   282→);\n   283→if (pos0Scored && pos0Scored.rawScore >= 0.05) {\n   284→  // ... fire protection\n   285→}\n   286→```\n   287→\n   288→Actually, checking: `pos0` is already in `selected`, meaning it already passed the threshold. The threshold is `max(0.08, bestThresholdScore * 0.7)`. So any candidate in `selected` has a meaningful score. The real question is whether \"Lato | Dania główne\" would be in `selected` at all.\n   289→\n   290→More robust guard: check if the position-0 candidate's **rawScore** is within a reasonable range of the ALL_CAPS candidate's rawScore (e.g., pos0.rawScore >= allCaps.rawScore * 0.5). A real title will have a comparable rawScore; a category header will have a much lower one.\n   291→\n   292→---\n   293→\n   294→## Change 4: Evaluation harness fix (out of scope for lib/text-classifier/)\n   295→\n   296→**Context:** Failure 4A (SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS — OCR reads \"/\" but expected title has \":\")\n   297→\n   298→The OCR text contains `\"/ COTTAGE CHEESE\"` where the printed book has `\": COTTAGE CHEESE\"`. The evaluation harness compares the extracted title against the filename-derived expected title. The filesystem may substitute `:` with `/` or vice versa, creating an impossible-to-match expected value.\n   299→\n   300→**Recommendation:** Normalize `/:` in the evaluation harness `titles_match` function. This is a change to `tools/title-loop/title-loop.py`, not to `lib/text-classifier/`. The algorithm is producing the correct output — it's the comparison that fails.\n   301→\n   302→---\n   303→\n   304→## Summary of Changes\n   305→\n   306→| Change | Target Failure | Files Modified | Risk | Complexity |\n   307→|--------|---------------|----------------|------|------------|\n   308→| Pre-merge continuation lines | F1 (Baked Eggs), F4B (SAFFRON join) | `title-extractor.ts` (`buildCandidates`) | Low — only affects lines starting with `/&+:(` | Low |\n   309→| Ingredient-gap in multi-title guard | F2 (CHLEBEK) | `title-extractor.ts` (multi-title guard block) | Medium — must not regress FINNISH | Medium |\n   310→| First-line mixed-case protection | F3 (Faszerowana papryka) | `title-extractor.ts` (after scoring, before multi-title guard) | Medium — needs rawScore guard for category headers | Medium |\n   311→| Eval harness separator normalization | F4A (SAFFRON OCR mismatch) | `title-loop.py` | None — eval-only change | Low |\n   312→\n   313→### Expected Accuracy After Changes\n   314→\n   315→- **Currently passing (4/8):** ARAYES SHRAK, FINNISH FLATBREADS, MIXED SEED CRISPBREAD, OVERNIGHT PIZZA DOUGH\n   316→- **Fixed by Change 1:** Baked Eggs ✓, SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS (partial — algorithm correct, eval still needs Change 4) ✓\n   317→- **Fixed by Change 2:** CHLEBEK ✓\n   318→- **Fixed by Change 3:** Faszerowana papryka ✓\n   319→- **Projected: 8/8 (100%)** with all changes including eval harness fix\n   320→\n   321→### Implementation Order\n   322→\n   323→1. **Change 1 (pre-merge)** — highest impact, lowest risk, fixes 2 failures\n   324→2. **Change 3 (first-line protection)** — independent of other changes, clear logic\n   325→3. **Change 2 (ingredient-gap)** — requires most careful testing against FINNISH FLATBREADS\n   326→4. **Change 4 (eval harness)** — trivial, independent\n   327→\n   328→### Tests to Add/Modify\n   329→\n   330→1. **New unit test:** \"merges continuation line starting with & into preceding line\" — verify `buildCandidates` produces merged candidate\n   331→2. **New unit test:** \"does not merge non-continuation second line\" — verify \"SHRAK\" (no leading symbol) is NOT pre-merged\n   332→3. **New unit test:** \"single recipe with ALL_CAPS section headers returns only title\" — CHLEBEK-style input\n   333→4. **New unit test:** \"bilingual page with mixed-case title at position 0 prefers it over ALL_CAPS subtitle\" — Faszerowana-style input\n   334→5. **Modify existing SAFFRON test** if the expected value needs updating for `/` vs `:`\n   335→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01UvcEb9Ss8NfNqSXXHwGaZ1","session_id":"f1cce918-fde6-46b5-9093-50476190ee9c","uuid":"296bbbed-3169-4f46-a7e0-7ccccef4c126"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01RFURbakd2iAWj9n4nNrYoA","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Iteration 9 — Improvement Plan\n     2→\n     3→## Summary\n     4→\n     5→One failure remains: `Faszerowana papryka.real.txt`. The algorithm returns `PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM` (Korean romanization at position 1) instead of `Faszerowana papryka` (Polish title at position 0). The fix is a targeted relaxation of the bilingual detection guard — no other code paths need to change.\n     6→\n     7→---\n     8→\n     9→## Root Cause Analysis\n    10→\n    11→### The bilingual detection condition is count-based when it should be position-based\n    12→\n    13→The pre-threshold bilingual suppression block (lines 390–395) was designed for exactly this pattern: a mixed-case title at position 0 followed by an ALL_CAPS foreign romanization at position ≤ 2. It correctly identifies `prePos0` (the mixed-case candidate at position 0) but then gates on `preAllCaps.length === 1` — requiring the *entire document* to contain exactly one ALL_CAPS candidate.\n    14→\n    15→This document has **four** ALL_CAPS candidates that pass `passesHardFilters`:\n    16→\n    17→| Candidate | Position | Role |\n    18→|---|---|---|\n    19→| `PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM` | 1 | Korean romanization (should be suppressed) |\n    20→| `NA 3 PAPRYKI` | 5 | Serving size |\n    21→| `SKŁADNIKI` | 9 | Section header |\n    22→| `WARZYWA` | 25 | Section header |\n    23→\n    24→Because `preAllCaps.length === 4`, the suppression does **not** fire. `PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM` enters scoring unsuppressed and accumulates +0.18 in bonuses (ALL_CAPS +0.08, structural heading +0.10) that overwhelm `Faszerowana papryka`'s position advantage.\n    25→\n    26→### Why this is a general pattern, not a one-off\n    27→\n    28→Polish recipe books routinely use ALL_CAPS for section headers (SKŁADNIKI, PRZYGOTOWANIE, WARZYWA) and serving info (NA 3 PAPRYKI). Any bilingual recipe page will have these alongside the foreign romanization, making `preAllCaps.length === 1` structurally impossible to satisfy. The count-based guard was written for a minimal case that doesn't occur in real documents.\n    29→\n    30→---\n    31→\n    32→## Proposed Fix\n    33→\n    34→### Replace count-based guard with positional + semantic check\n    35→\n    36→**Current code (lines 390–395):**\n    37→```typescript\n    38→const prePos0 = scored.find((s) => s.position === 0 && !isAllCaps(s.text));\n    39→const preAllCaps = scored.filter((s) => isAllCaps(s.text));\n    40→if (prePos0 && preAllCaps.length === 1 && preAllCaps[0].position <= 2) {\n    41→  const capsLower = preAllCaps[0].text.toLowerCase();\n    42→  scoredForThreshold = scored.filter((s) => !s.text.toLowerCase().startsWith(capsLower));\n    43→}\n    44→```\n    45→\n    46→**Proposed code:**\n    47→```typescript\n    48→const prePos0 = scored.find((s) => s.position === 0 && !isAllCaps(s.text));\n    49→if (prePos0) {\n    50→  // Find ALL_CAPS candidates at position ≤ 2 (immediately after mixed-case title)\n    51→  const nearbyAllCaps = scored.filter(\n    52→    (s) => isAllCaps(s.text) && s.position >= 1 && s.position <= 2\n    53→  );\n    54→  // Check if any nearby ALL_CAPS candidate is semantically close to the position-0\n    55→  // candidate — indicating it's a translation/romanization of the same dish name.\n    56→  // Use the already-computed embeddings from rawScored.\n    57→  const pos0Embedding = rawScored.find((r) => r.text === prePos0.text)?.embedding;\n    58→  if (pos0Embedding) {\n    59→    const translationCandidates = nearbyAllCaps.filter((cap) => {\n    60→      const capEmbedding = rawScored.find((r) => r.text === cap.text)?.embedding;\n    61→      if (!capEmbedding) return false;\n    62→      const sim = cosineSimilarity(pos0Embedding, capEmbedding);\n    63→      return sim > 0.4;\n    64→    });\n    65→    if (translationCandidates.length > 0) {\n    66→      const suppressTexts = new Set(translationCandidates.map((t) => t.text.toLowerCase()));\n    67→      scoredForThreshold = scored.filter((s) => !suppressTexts.has(s.text.toLowerCase()));\n    68→    }\n    69→  }\n    70→}\n    71→```\n    72→\n    73→### Why this works\n    74→\n    75→1. **Positional check** (`position >= 1 && position <= 2`): Only considers ALL_CAPS candidates immediately after the mixed-case title. Section headers at position 9, 25 are irrelevant — they can't be bilingual translations of the title.\n    76→\n    77→2. **Semantic similarity check** (`cosineSimilarity > 0.4`): Both `Faszerowana papryka` and `PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM` are dish names. Their embeddings will be close because they refer to the same concept (a paprika dish). This distinguishes a translation from an unrelated ALL_CAPS line that happens to appear at position 1–2 (unlikely but possible).\n    78→\n    79→3. **No new embedding calls**: Both candidates already have embeddings computed in the rawScored pass. We reuse them, adding zero latency.\n    80→\n    81→4. **Suppression scope**: Only the translation candidate is removed from `scoredForThreshold` — all other candidates (including other ALL_CAPS section headers) remain in the pool. This is narrower and safer than the current approach which removes anything starting with the caps candidate's text.\n    82→\n    83→### What changes\n    84→\n    85→| Aspect | Before | After |\n    86→|---|---|---|\n    87→| Guard condition | `preAllCaps.length === 1` (global count) | `nearbyAllCaps` at position ≤ 2 (local) |\n    88→| Validation | None (position ≤ 2 only) | Position ≤ 2 AND embedding similarity > 0.4 |\n    89→| Suppression target | Anything starting with the single ALL_CAPS text | Exact match on confirmed translation candidates |\n    90→| Handles multiple section headers | No (breaks when count > 1) | Yes (ignores distant ALL_CAPS entirely) |\n    91→\n    92→### What does NOT change\n    93→\n    94→- Hard filters, candidate generation, merge logic — all untouched\n    95→- Scoring bonuses (ALL_CAPS +0.08, structural heading +0.10) — unchanged\n    96→- Dedup logic, multi-title guard, continuation join protection — unchanged\n    97→- Threshold computation formula — unchanged\n    98→- Empty-pool fallback — unchanged\n    99→\n   100→---\n   101→\n   102→## Edge Cases and Regression Safety\n   103→\n   104→### Case: Bilingual page with no section headers (original minimal case)\n   105→Before: `preAllCaps.length === 1` fires. After: `nearbyAllCaps` finds the same single candidate, similarity > 0.4 (both are dish names), suppression fires. **Same result.**\n   106→\n   107→### Case: ALL_CAPS title at position 0, mixed-case subtitle at position 1\n   108→`prePos0` requires `!isAllCaps(s.text)`, so if position 0 is ALL_CAPS, the block doesn't activate. **No change.**\n   109→\n   110→### Case: Mixed-case at position 0, unrelated ALL_CAPS at position 1\n   111→If the ALL_CAPS candidate at position 1 is semantically unrelated (e.g., \"SERVES 4\" that somehow passed filters), its embedding similarity to the position-0 candidate will be low (< 0.4). The block won't suppress it. **Safe.**\n   112→\n   113→### Case: No mixed-case at position 0\n   114→`prePos0` is undefined, entire block is skipped. **No change.**\n   115→\n   116→---\n   117→\n   118→## Similarity Threshold Justification (0.4)\n   119→\n   120→The threshold of 0.4 is deliberately low because:\n   121→- Two dish names referring to the same recipe (even in different languages) typically have cosine similarity 0.5–0.8 with MiniLM, because the food concept (paprika, eggs, etc.) overlaps strongly.\n   122→- A dish name vs. a section header (\"SKŁADNIKI\", \"PRZYGOTOWANIE\") typically has similarity 0.15–0.35, because they share no food-concept overlap.\n   123→- 0.4 sits cleanly in the gap between these distributions.\n   124→\n   125→If the gap turns out to be narrower for some language pairs, the threshold can be raised to 0.5 without losing this case (PAPRIKA/papryka share a cognate root, so similarity will be well above 0.5).\n   126→\n   127→---\n   128→\n   129→## Implementation Checklist\n   130→\n   131→1. Replace the bilingual detection block at lines 389–395 in `title-extractor.ts`\n   132→2. No new imports needed (`cosineSimilarity` already imported, `rawScored` embeddings already available)\n   133→3. No new embedding calls (zero performance impact)\n   134→4. Run existing test suite to confirm no regressions\n   135→5. Run title-loop evaluation to confirm `Faszerowana papryka` now returns correctly\n   136→\n   137→---\n   138→\n   139→## Expected Impact\n   140→\n   141→| Metric | Before | After |\n   142→|---|---|---|\n   143→| Passing cases | 7/8 (87.5%) | 8/8 (100%) |\n   144→| New embedding calls | 0 | 0 |\n   145→| Lines changed | ~6 lines replaced | ~15 lines replacement |\n   146→| Risk of regression | — | Low (strictly narrower suppression scope, with semantic validation gate) |\n   147→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01UvcEb9Ss8NfNqSXXHwGaZ1","session_id":"f1cce918-fde6-46b5-9093-50476190ee9c","uuid":"92f7e411-1e80-4b75-82b0-8c523c13b5e4"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01LP47TvhucT4DMcKy9Uu9wk","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Iteration 9 — Failure Analysis\n     2→\n     3→## Failing case\n     4→\n     5→- **File**: `Faszerowana papryka.real.txt`\n     6→- **Expected**: `Faszerowana papryka`\n     7→- **Got**: `PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM`\n     8→\n     9→---\n    10→\n    11→## Document structure\n    12→\n    13→```\n    14→Line 0: Faszerowana papryka          ← correct Polish title (mixed-case)\n    15→Line 1: PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM          ← ALL_CAPS Korean romanization\n    16→Line 2: 파프리카 계란찜               ← Korean script (filtered out)\n    17→Line 3: Ten bardzo prosty przepis…   ← body text\n    18→Line 5: NA 3 PAPRYKI                 ← ALL_CAPS serving size\n    19→Line 9: SKŁADNIKI                    ← ALL_CAPS section header\n    20→Line 25: WARZYWA                     ← ALL_CAPS section header\n    21→```\n    22→\n    23→---\n    24→\n    25→## Why the failure occurs\n    26→\n    27→### 1. Bilingual detection condition is too strict\n    28→\n    29→The algorithm has a pre-threshold bilingual suppression block (lines 390–395) designed exactly for this pattern: a mixed-case title at position 0 followed by an ALL_CAPS foreign romanization. It fires when:\n    30→\n    31→```typescript\n    32→prePos0 && preAllCaps.length === 1 && preAllCaps[0].position <= 2\n    33→```\n    34→\n    35→The condition `preAllCaps.length === 1` requires that the document contains **exactly one** ALL_CAPS candidate. This document has four ALL_CAPS candidates that pass `passesHardFilters`:\n    36→\n    37→| Candidate | Position | Why it survives |\n    38→|---|---|---|\n    39→| `PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM` | 1 | All uppercase letters, two words |\n    40→| `NA 3 PAPRYKI` | 5 | All uppercase letters, passes vowel/length checks |\n    41→| `SKŁADNIKI` | 9 | Polish word, Ł stripped, remaining letters all uppercase |\n    42→| `WARZYWA` | 25 | All uppercase, passes all hard filters |\n    43→\n    44→Because `preAllCaps.length === 4`, the bilingual suppression does **not** fire. `PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM` enters the scoring pipeline unsuppressed.\n    45→\n    46→### 2. PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM accumulates decisive bonuses\n    47→\n    48→`PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM` passes `isStructuralHeading` (two words, both ≥4 uppercase alpha letters). It is selected as `firstStructuralHeading` and receives:\n    49→\n    50→- **ALL_CAPS bonus**: +0.08\n    51→- **Structural heading bonus**: +0.10\n    52→- **Position factor** ≈ ×1.11 (position 1, near top)\n    53→\n    54→Total additive bonus: **+0.18** above its raw embedding score.\n    55→\n    56→`Faszerowana papryka` receives:\n    57→\n    58→- **Position factor** ≈ ×1.12 (position 0)\n    59→- No ALL_CAPS bonus (mixed-case)\n    60→- No structural heading bonus\n    61→\n    62→Even if `Faszerowana papryka` has a meaningfully better raw embedding similarity to the title reference, the 0.18-point bonus gap is large enough that `PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM` wins.\n    63→\n    64→### 3. `PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM` semantically resembles a recipe title\n    65→\n    66→The Korean romanization `PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM` is a legitimate dish name. Its embedding similarity to the title reference (\"recipe name, dish title, nazwa dania\") is plausibly competitive with `Faszerowana papryka`, so even the raw embedding signal doesn't cleanly favour the correct answer.\n    67→\n    68→---\n    69→\n    70→## Root cause\n    71→\n    72→The bilingual detection was written for the minimal case: one mixed-case title plus one ALL_CAPS romanization, nothing else. Real-world recipes routinely include additional ALL_CAPS lines for section headers (SKŁADNIKI, WARZYWA, PRZYGOTOWANIE) and serving sizes (NA 3 PAPRYKI). These innocuous lines break the `preAllCaps.length === 1` guard and disable the suppression entirely.\n    73→\n    74→---\n    75→\n    76→## Pattern generalisation\n    77→\n    78→The failure belongs to the class: **bilingual recipe page with structural ALL_CAPS section headers**. The correct heuristic is not \"exactly one ALL_CAPS candidate exists\" but rather \"the ALL_CAPS candidate immediately after position-0 appears to be a romanization/translation of the mixed-case title, regardless of how many other ALL_CAPS lines exist elsewhere in the document\". A positional check (is the ALL_CAPS candidate at position ≤ 2?) combined with a semantic proximity check (does it embed close to the mixed-case candidate?) would be more robust than the count-based guard.\n    79→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01UvcEb9Ss8NfNqSXXHwGaZ1","session_id":"f1cce918-fde6-46b5-9093-50476190ee9c","uuid":"10515273-6669-421a-b4b8-776fe80c3fe0"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_014EGDk8Q1nsgSYE2PdDhgR8","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Iteration 9 Improvement Plan\n     2→\n     3→## Summary\n     4→\n     5→Two failures, two distinct root causes that share a common theme: the threshold gate has absolute veto power over candidates that pass all structural/hard filters, with no fallback when the candidate pool is small or the positional signal is unambiguous.\n     6→\n     7→The fixes are:\n     8→\n     9→1. **Pre-threshold bilingual protection** — move first-line detection before threshold filtering so ALL_CAPS bonuses can't inflate the threshold beyond the mixed-case title's reach.\n    10→2. **Empty-pool fallback** — when threshold filtering discards every candidate, fall back to the best positional candidate from the hard-filter-passing pool.\n    11→\n    12→These are complementary: fix 1 prevents failure 2 (Faszerowana papryka) by keeping the correct candidate in `selected`; fix 2 prevents failure 1 (Baked Eggs) by ensuring a sole survivor is never silently discarded.\n    13→\n    14→---\n    15→\n    16→## Failure 1: \"Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce & Coriander\" → `''`\n    17→\n    18→### Root Cause\n    19→\n    20→The pre-merge step correctly produces the full candidate. It passes all hard filters (54 chars, no measurements, no metadata, not garbled). But the embedding scorer computes `rawScore = titleSim - max(headerSim, noiseSim)` and because ingredient words (Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce, Coriander) are semantically close to `HEADER_REFERENCE` (\"ingredients list, cooking directions\"), `headerSim ≈ titleSim` or `headerSim > titleSim`. The rawScore is near zero or negative. No bonus applies (mixed-case, not structural heading). The final score falls below `threshold = max(0.08, ...)` and the candidate is filtered out, returning `undefined`.\n    21→\n    22→The fundamental issue: **embeddings cannot distinguish \"dish named after its ingredients\" from \"fragment of an ingredient list\"**. The hard filters already make that distinction (ingredient lists have measurements, start with numbers, etc.), but their verdict is overruled by the embedding threshold.\n    23→\n    24→### Fix: Empty-pool fallback\n    25→\n    26→After the existing threshold filter (`let selected = scored.filter(s => s.score >= threshold)`), add a fallback:\n    27→\n    28→```typescript\n    29→// BEFORE (line ~389):\n    30→let selected = scored.filter((s) => s.score >= threshold);\n    31→\n    32→// AFTER:\n    33→let selected = scored.filter((s) => s.score >= threshold);\n    34→\n    35→// Empty-pool fallback: when threshold filtering discards every candidate,\n    36→// the hard filters' structural verdict should not be overruled by weak\n    37→// embedding differentiation. Return the best positional candidate.\n    38→if (selected.length === 0 && scored.length > 0) {\n    39→  // Prefer candidates near the top of the document (position 0 = most likely title).\n    40→  // Among ties, prefer higher score.\n    41→  const fallback = scored\n    42→    .slice()\n    43→    .sort((a, b) => a.position - b.position || b.score - a.score);\n    44→  selected = [fallback[0]];\n    45→}\n    46→```\n    47→\n    48→**Why this is safe:** Every candidate in `scored` already passed `passesHardFilters()` — no measurements, no metadata, no garbled text, not starting with a number, not lowercase-initial. If the entire pool of structurally-valid candidates has weak embedding differentiation, position is the strongest remaining signal (recipe titles appear at the top of the page). This fallback only fires when `selected` would otherwise be empty, so it cannot degrade any currently-passing test.\n    49→\n    50→### Expected behavior after fix\n    51→\n    52→- \"Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce & Coriander\" is the only candidate in `scored` (the body text, ingredients, and metadata all fail hard filters).\n    53→- Threshold filter discards it (score < 0.08).\n    54→- Fallback selects it as the sole candidate → returns the correct title.\n    55→\n    56→---\n    57→\n    58→## Failure 2: \"Faszerowana papryka\" → `'PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM'`\n    59→\n    60→### Root Cause\n    61→\n    62→The first-line protection (lines 468–479) was designed for exactly this case: mixed-case title at position 0 followed by ALL_CAPS subtitle. But the protection runs **after** threshold filtering. The ALL_CAPS candidate \"PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM\" receives `+0.08` allCapsBonus + `+0.10` structuralBonus = `+0.18` on top of its rawScore. This inflates the threshold via `bestThresholdScore * 0.7`. The Polish mixed-case title \"Faszerowana papryka\" has a low rawScore (MiniLM is English-centric; short Polish text has low cosine similarity to the English TITLE_REFERENCE) and no bonuses. It falls below the inflated threshold, never enters `selected`, and the protection — which checks `selected.find(s => s.position === 0)` — silently becomes a no-op.\n    63→\n    64→The design is self-defeating: the protection requires the correct title to have already survived the threshold independently, but it's needed precisely when the title **cannot** survive the threshold.\n    65→\n    66→### Fix: Pre-threshold bilingual detection\n    67→\n    68→Move the bilingual detection to operate on the full `scored` array (before threshold filtering). When the pattern is detected, force-include the position-0 candidate and suppress the ALL_CAPS subtitle.\n    69→\n    70→```typescript\n    71→// BEFORE (lines 385-389):\n    72→const bestThresholdScore = Math.max(...scored.map((s) => s.thresholdScore));\n    73→const threshold = Math.max(0.08, bestThresholdScore * 0.7);\n    74→let selected = scored.filter((s) => s.score >= threshold);\n    75→\n    76→// AFTER:\n    77→// --- Pre-threshold bilingual title detection ---\n    78→// When a mixed-case candidate at position 0 is followed by a single ALL_CAPS\n    79→// candidate at position ≤ 2 in the FULL scored pool, this is a bilingual recipe\n    80→// page (e.g., Polish title + ALL_CAPS Korean romanization). Suppress the ALL_CAPS\n    81→// candidate before computing threshold so its bonuses don't inflate the threshold\n    82→// beyond the mixed-case title's reach.\n    83→//\n    84→// This replaces the post-threshold guard at lines 468-479 which was ineffective\n    85→// because it required both candidates to survive threshold independently.\n    86→let scoredForThreshold = scored;\n    87→const prePos0 = scored.find((s) => s.position === 0 && !isAllCaps(s.text));\n    88→const preAllCaps = scored.filter((s) => isAllCaps(s.text));\n    89→if (\n    90→  prePos0 &&\n    91→  preAllCaps.length === 1 &&\n    92→  preAllCaps[0].position <= 2\n    93→) {\n    94→  // Remove the ALL_CAPS subtitle from threshold computation AND from selection.\n    95→  scoredForThreshold = scored.filter((s) => s !== preAllCaps[0]);\n    96→}\n    97→\n    98→const bestThresholdScore = Math.max(...scoredForThreshold.map((s) => s.thresholdScore));\n    99→const threshold = Math.max(0.08, bestThresholdScore * 0.7);\n   100→let selected = scoredForThreshold.filter((s) => s.score >= threshold);\n   101→```\n   102→\n   103→Then **remove or disable** the old post-threshold first-line protection (lines 468–479) since it's now redundant.\n   104→\n   105→**Why this is safe:**\n   106→- The guard condition is identical to the old one: mixed-case at position 0, exactly 1 ALL_CAPS candidate at position ≤ 2.\n   107→- `preAllCaps.length === 1` ensures it never fires on genuine multi-recipe pages (which have ≥ 2 ALL_CAPS headings).\n   108→- Moving it pre-threshold only changes behavior when the mixed-case title would otherwise be below threshold — which is precisely the failure case.\n   109→\n   110→### Expected behavior after fix\n   111→\n   112→- `scored` contains \"Faszerowana papryka\" (pos 0, mixed-case) and \"PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM\" (pos 1, ALL_CAPS).\n   113→- Pre-threshold detection identifies the bilingual pattern: pos0 is mixed-case, exactly 1 ALL_CAPS at pos ≤ 2.\n   114→- \"PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM\" is removed from `scoredForThreshold`.\n   115→- Threshold is now computed from \"Faszerowana papryka\" alone — much lower, achievable.\n   116→- \"Faszerowana papryka\" enters `selected` → returned as the title.\n   117→\n   118→---\n   119→\n   120→## Interaction between the two fixes\n   121→\n   122→The fixes are independent and non-conflicting:\n   123→\n   124→| Scenario | Fix 1 (fallback) | Fix 2 (bilingual) | Which fires? |\n   125→|---|---|---|---|\n   126→| Baked Eggs (sole candidate, below threshold) | Catches it | N/A (no ALL_CAPS) | Fix 1 |\n   127→| Faszerowana papryka (bilingual, threshold inflated) | Would also catch it as fallback | Prevents the problem entirely | Fix 2 (fix 1 is not needed) |\n   128→| Normal recipes (candidates above threshold) | Never fires | Never fires (no pattern match or >1 ALL_CAPS) | Neither |\n   129→| Multi-recipe ALL_CAPS pages | Never fires (candidates pass threshold) | Never fires (≥2 ALL_CAPS) | Neither |\n   130→\n   131→Fix 2 is the primary fix for failure 2. Fix 1 is the primary fix for failure 1. But fix 1 would also serve as a secondary safety net for failure 2 if fix 2 somehow didn't fire — defense in depth.\n   132→\n   133→---\n   134→\n   135→## Changes to make (ordered)\n   136→\n   137→### Change 1: Pre-threshold bilingual detection\n   138→**File:** `lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts`\n   139→**Location:** Before line 385 (threshold computation)\n   140→**Action:** Add bilingual detection on full `scored` array. Suppress the sole ALL_CAPS subtitle from threshold computation and selection when the pattern matches.\n   141→\n   142→### Change 2: Empty-pool fallback\n   143→**File:** `lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts`\n   144→**Location:** After line 389 (`let selected = scored.filter(...)`)\n   145→**Action:** Add fallback that selects the best positional candidate when `selected` is empty.\n   146→\n   147→### Change 3: Remove old post-threshold first-line protection\n   148→**File:** `lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts`\n   149→**Location:** Lines 468–479\n   150→**Action:** Remove the entire block. It's replaced by the pre-threshold version (change 1) and was ineffective in the failure case anyway.\n   151→\n   152→### No other changes needed\n   153→\n   154→- Hard filters: working correctly for both cases.\n   155→- Pre-merge continuation logic: working correctly (Baked Eggs candidate is correctly merged).\n   156→- Multi-title guard: not involved in either failure.\n   157→- Dedup logic: not involved in either failure.\n   158→- Structural heading detection: not involved in failure 1; correctly identifies PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM in failure 2 but this is handled by the bilingual guard.\n   159→\n   160→---\n   161→\n   162→## Risk Assessment\n   163→\n   164→**Risk of regression on passing tests:**\n   165→- **Low.** Fix 1 (fallback) only fires when `selected` is empty — this never happens for currently-passing tests. Fix 2 (bilingual) only fires when there's a mixed-case pos-0 with exactly 1 ALL_CAPS at pos ≤ 2 — this pattern doesn't appear in currently-passing tests (they have either 0 or ≥2 ALL_CAPS headings, or no mixed-case at pos 0).\n   166→\n   167→**Risk of over-fitting:**\n   168→- **Moderate but acceptable.** The bilingual guard is specific to a real pattern (bilingual cookbooks) rather than a one-off hack. The empty-pool fallback is a general safety net that addresses a genuine design gap (hard filters should not be overruled by weak embedding signals).\n   169→\n   170→**What could still go wrong:**\n   171→- A recipe where position 0 is genuinely not the title (e.g., book name on first line, recipe title on line 3). The fallback would return the wrong line. Mitigation: this is rare in the test corpus and the hard filters would likely catch book names (too long, or garbled).\n   172→- A recipe where position 0 is mixed-case and position 1 is ALL_CAPS but the ALL_CAPS line is the real title (not a subtitle). The bilingual guard would suppress it. Mitigation: the `position ≤ 2` and `length === 1` constraints are very specific.\n   173→\n   174→## Expected accuracy after changes\n   175→\n   176→- Iteration 8: 75% (6/8 passing, 2 failing)\n   177→- Projected: **100% (8/8 passing)** — both failures addressed with targeted, non-overlapping fixes.\n   178→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01UvcEb9Ss8NfNqSXXHwGaZ1","session_id":"f1cce918-fde6-46b5-9093-50476190ee9c","uuid":"29b6a615-7315-49bb-967f-3bf49e5d7444"}
