{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01Y6rGtHYW6hjDhikif1js8D","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"So the two new test files (Kimchi, MŁODE PORY) aren't in the results yet. Let me now trace through the logic for both failures carefully.\n\n**Failure 1: CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM**\n\nThe input has ~36 lines. Let me trace through `buildCandidates`:\n\nNon-empty lines after trimming:\n0: \"Lato | Dania główne\" \n1: \"CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM\"\n2: \"WARZYWA I BOCZEK\"\n3: \"500 g strączków zielonego groszku\" — starts with digit, fails hardFilter\n\n\n4-7: More ingredient lines starting with quantities, all filtered out\n8: \"CHLEBEK\" — passes, added as candidate\n9-11: More ingredient lines with quantities, filtered\n12: \"só1\" — too short and garbled, filtered\n13: Truncated line that I need to continue examining\n\nLooking at the next chunk, I can see line 13 continues as \"eżo zmielony pieprz\" which is garbled text, then we move into section headers like \"Przygotowanie warzyw i boczku\" and \"Gotowanie warzyw\" that pass the filter. There are timing and serving details (\"DLA 4 OSÓB\", \"PRZYGOTOWANIE 1 GODZ. 45 MIN\", etc.) that also pass, along with more section headers like \"Przygotowanie chlebka\" and various body text entries that contain sentence breaks and are therefore filtered out as garbled.\n\nNow I'm checking whether the opening line \"Lato | Dania główne\" passes the hard filters — it's 19 characters, doesn't look like an ingredient or metadata, and when I extract just the letters and check for vowel density, it seems to be legitimate text rather than garbled content. \"Lato | Dania główne\" passes the hard filters, so it's a valid candidate. Looking at the other entries, \"CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM\" is all caps with five words, which also clears the checks.\n\nBut the feedback indicates this entry should have six words, not five. Let me recount the actual text more carefully to see where the discrepancy is.\n\nActually, wait—if the word count is truly five, then the pre-filter should treat it favorably since it's checking for `wordCount <= 5`. That would give it a sort value of 0, meaning it should be prioritized rather than penalized. Let me look more closely at how the sorting logic actually works here.\n\nThe code is implementing a two-tier sort: first it prioritizes all-caps entries, then within those tiers it prioritizes shorter entries with five words or fewer. So \"CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM\" should rank high on both criteria.\n\nLet me recount the words manually — there are four spaces between the five words, so it's definitely five words, not six. The feedback might be analyzing a different version of the code, or there's something about how the word counting function works that I'm missing.\n\nRegardless, the core issue the feedback points to is that the 25-candidate pre-filter is cutting off the actual title before it can be properly sorted. Even if the word count is five and should qualify for priority zero, something about the filtering mechanism is preventing it from being considered. The issue is likely one of two things: either the pre-filter is removing the full title, or the dedup logic is keeping the shorter \"CHLEBEK\" and discarding the longer version. Since \"CHLEBEK\" is only one word, it wouldn't qualify as a structural heading anyway. Looking at the dedup filter, it removes any item if a shorter substring of it already exists in the selection—so if \"CHLEBEK\" somehow made it through, it would eliminate the full title \"CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM\" since the shorter text is contained within it.\n\nThe real problem is in the prefix filter around line 440, which should be filtering out \"CHLEBEK\" when the complete title is present. But that only works if both candidates make it into the selection first. Let me trace through what should happen: if the pre-filter correctly includes the five-word full title, then both versions end up as candidates, get embedded and scored, and the longer one with all-caps words should rank higher.\n\nNow I'm checking the `isStructuralHeading` logic to see if the full title qualifies...\n\nit passes all the checks: it's all caps, has enough words, and the significant words (those with multiple uppercase letters) all meet the minimum length requirement. So \"CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM\" would indeed be treated as a structural heading, which means it gets the bonus and the prefix filter strips \"CHLEBEK\" from it.\n\nBut wait—the feedback claims it has 6 words when I'm counting 5. That discrepancy matters because the pre-filter sorts all-caps candidates with 5 or fewer words differently than those with more. If it's actually 5 words, it should rank higher and get kept. Let me figure out where the word count disagreement is coming from.\n\nI'm checking the actual word count function to see how it splits the text. It splits on whitespace and filters out empty strings, which gives me 5 words for that phrase. So the feedback's analysis about the word count seems off—the pre-filter shouldn't be penalizing it based on word count alone. I need to look at the actual logs to understand what's really happening.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":257,"cache_read_input_tokens":40211,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":257},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"f1cce918-fde6-46b5-9093-50476190ee9c","uuid":"3976b7a1-85fe-476f-ac33-5fd999588447"}
