l heading with its 2 significant words, and I need to verify how metadata-like entries like \"DLA 4 OSÓB\" are being filtered, since the logic checks if significant words exceed a certain length threshold. OCZKIEM\" and \"WARZYWA I BOCZEK\". Whichever structural heading scores highest becomes the `firstStructuralHeading`, and then the prefix filter removes any candidates that are space-delimited prefixes of it—so if \"WARZYWA I BOCZEK\" wins, \"WARZYWA\" would get filtered out.\n\nNow in the multi-title guard, I'm checking if there are multiple ALL_CAPS survivors. \"CHLEBEK\" wouldn't be filtered as a prefix of \"WARZYWA I BOCZEK\" since they don't have that relationship, so it stays in the pool. When the allCapsSelected count hits 2 or more, the logic examines whether non-first ALL_CAPS headings are actually sub-headers by looking at what follows them—if \"WARZYWA I BOCZEK\" is followed by ingredient lines like \"500 g strączków zielonego groszku\", that signals it's a sub-header rather than a main title.\n\nFor \"DLA 4 OSÓB\" at position 20, the next lines are timing instructions like \"PRZYGOTOWANIE 1 GODZ. 45 MIN\" and \"GOTOWANIE 30 MIN\"—these don't look like ingredients since they lack measurement units or digit-starting patterns, and the ingredient detection logic wouldn't catch \"MIN\" as a measurement unit since it's not in the standard patterns list.\n\nSince not all caps headings are followed by ingredients, `isSubHeader` becomes false and the code falls back to using `allCapsSelected`. Then the deduplication logic runs, removing \"CHLEBEK\" since it's a substring of the longer \"CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM\".\n\nThe prefix filter was supposed to catch this, but it only works when the correct title is marked as `firstStructuralHeading` — if a different heading like \"WARZYWA I BOCZEK\" gets selected instead, the filter removes the wrong prefixes, leaving the substring to corrupt the final result.\n\nLet me trace through the actual order of operations to see where the logic breaks down. So `firstStructuralHeading` tries to find a candidate that continues the baseHeading with a special character, but if none exists, it just uses baseHeading itself. In this case, if baseHeading is \"CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM\", there's no matching continuation, so it falls back to that same heading.\n\nNow I'm comparing which heading would score higher: the full dish name \"CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM\" (bread with vegetables and bacon) versus just \"WARZYWA I BOCZEK\" (vegetables and bacon). The full dish name has more content words and should match better against the title reference using MiniLM embeddings, giving it a stronger rawScore.\n\nBut wait—if \"CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM\" is the structural heading, the prefix filter should catch \"CHLEBEK\" and remove it before dedup runs, which would prevent the wrong output. Since the test shows \"CHLEBEK\" is actually appearing in the output, something must be failing—maybe the threshold check is rejecting the full heading, or the scoring isn't working as expected. bestThresholdScore is high (say driven by an ALL_CAPS candidate with bonus), the threshold could be high enough that \"CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM\" fails.\n\nWait — \"CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM\" itself is ALL_CAPS and gets the allCapsBonus. And if it's `firstStructuralHeading`, it gets the structural bonus too. Its score = rawScore * positionFactor + allCapsBonus + structuralBonus. It should be one of the highest-scoring candidates.\n\nUnless... the pre-filter actually DOES cut it. Let me reconsider whether there could be > 25 ALL_CAPS candidates with ≤5 words. I'm counting the individual ALL_CAPS lines that qualify: \"CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM\", \"WARZYWA I BOCZEK\", \"CHLEBEK\", \"DLA 4 OSÓB\", \"PRZYGOTOWANIE 1 GODZ. 45 MIN\", \"GOTOWANIE 30 MIN\", and \"OCZEKIWANIE 1 GODZ. 30 MIN\" — that's 7 so far. Now I need to check if joining consecutive ALL_CAPS lines creates additional candidates that would push past the 25-candidate threshold. Looking at what happens when I try to join \"CHLEBEK\" with the next line — it's \"500 g mąki\", which isn't all caps, so that join fails the ingredient check. Same problem with other potential two-line combinations like \"WARZYWA I BOCZEK\" plus measurement text. So I'm left with around 7 all-caps lines that are 5 words or fewer as single candidates, plus some longer all-caps joins that would be tier 2, which is well under the 25-line threshold. This means the title candidate should pass the pre-filter regardless.\n\nLet me trace through the actual logic: if \"CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM\" becomes the first structural heading and passes the threshold, the prefix filter should remove \"CHLEBEK\" since it's a space-delimited prefix of the full phrase. Then dedup runs, but \"CHLEBEK\" is already gone. The multi-title guard should let \"CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM\" win. This should work, so I'm puzzled why the test returns just \"CHLEBEK\".\n\nI think the feedback's analysis about how the sorting prioritizes shorter word counts might actually be correct — I should probably run the test to see what's really happening rather than relying on my skepticism.\n\nWait, let me recount the words in \"CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM\" one more time: that's CHLEBEK, Z, WARZYWAMI, I, BOCZKIEM — exactly 5 words when split by whitespace. Unless there's trailing whitespace creating an empty element after filtering, but that seems unlikely.\n\nSo the title shouldn't be penalized for word count. But the test is returning just \"CHLEBEK\" instead of the full title, which suggests a different mechanism is at play. Maybe the structural bonus is going to a different candidate entirely — perhaps \"WARZYWA I BOCZEK\" is scoring higher in the embedding model because it's shorter and more directly food-related, which would give it the structural bonus and push it ahead.\n\nIf that's the case, then the prefix filter only checks against that winning structural candidate, not against all the other structural options. \"CHLEBEK\" wouldn't be filtered out as a prefix of \"WARZYWA I BOCZEK\", so it survives to deduplication. But then during dedup, since \"CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM\" contains the shorter \"CHLEBEK\", the longer version gets removed and \"CHLEBEK\" wins — which matches the test result. This is probably what's actually happening: the prefix filter is too narrow in scope, only protecting against prefixes of the top structural heading rather than all structural candidates.\n\nFor the second failure with \"Faszerowana papryka\", the problem is that \"NA 3 PAPRYKI\" isn't being filtered out as metadata, and the ALL_CAPS bonus is letting it win instead.\n\nI need to think through solutions. For the \"CHLEBEK\" issue, the core problem is that substring dedup removes the real title when a section header happens to be a substring of it. Rather than adding another fragile pre-filter, I should flip the dedup logic: when a single-line ALL_CAPS structural heading candidate is a substring of another ALL_CAPS candidate, prefer the longer one instead of the shorter one.\n\nOr more fundamentally, the \"shorter wins\" dedup rule breaks down when the shorter candidate is actually a document sub-header. If \"CHLEBEK\" is followed immediately by ingredient lines, it's a section header, not a title, and should be filtered out. I could extend the sub-header detection that already exists in the multi-title guard to also run during the dedup stage. The simplest approach might be to just remove single-word ALL_CAPS candidates that are substrings of multi-word ALL_CAPS candidates before scoring even happens. Option 3 feels most robust though—filtering out ALL_CAPS candidates that look like section headers based on what follows them.\n\nLet me trace through this: \"WARZYWA I BOCZEK\" at position 2 is followed by an ingredient line, so it gets removed. \"CHLEBEK\" at position 8 is also followed by an ingredient, so it's removed too. That leaves \"CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM\" at position 1, which is followed by \"WARZYWA I BOCZEK\" (not an ingredient), so it survives as the title.\n\nThe real problem is that the dedup stage at line 489 runs before the multi-title guard at line 504, which already tries to collapse multiple ALL_CAPS entries. I need to either move the sub-header detection before dedup or add a pre-dedup filter that strips out ALL_CAPS lines that are followed by ingredients.\n\nFor the Faszerowana papryka failure, \"NA 3 PAPRYKI\" isn't recognized as metadata and beats the correct mixed-case title because of the all-caps bonus. I should extend `looksLikeMetadata` to catch Polish serving size patterns like \"NA\\s+\\d+\" (meaning \"FOR N...\").\n\nBut I'm realizing that Polish prep and cooking time patterns like \"PRZYGOTOWANIE\\s+\\d+\", \"GOTOWANIE\\s+\\d+\", and \"OCZEKIWANIE\\s+\\d+\" also show up in the CHLEBEK case. If I filter these as metadata, they get removed from the candidate pool entirely, which actually solves both failures at once by reducing the number of ALL_CAPS entries competing for the title. So the straightforward solution is to add these Polish metadata patterns to the filter.\n\nThe trickier part is the CHLEBEK case itself. Even after filtering metadata, \"CHLEBEK\" as a sub-section header can still eliminate \"CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM\" through dedup if \"WARZYWA I BOCZEK\" ends up in the structural heading slot. I need a smarter dedup strategy—maybe one that prefers longer, multi-word ALL_CAPS candidates over shorter single-word ones when the longer version looks like a proper heading.\n\nActually, the simplest fix is to detect sub-section headers before dedup runs: if a short ALL_CAPS candidate is immediately followed by ingredient lines in the source, it's a recipe section, not the title, so remove it first. Combined with better Polish metadata detection, this should handle both failure cases.\n\nBut I need to be careful about moving sub-header detection earlier—the existing logic at line 504 already handles this for multi-recipe pages like ARAYES SHRAK and the Finnish flatbreads case. Shifting this check before dedup could change how those cases behave, so I should think through what the safest approach is here.\n\nActually, a more targeted fix would be to refine the dedup rule itself: when deciding whether to remove a substring candidate, make an exception if that candidate is a demonstrable sub-section header—meaning it's a single ALL_CAPS phrase followed by ingredient-like lines in the source. In that case, remove the longer candidate instead. This keeps the logic conservative and only fires when both candidates survive the earlier filters.\n\nLet me also consider what other test inputs might have similar patterns to watch out for. I'm noticing the OCR has introduced some typos in the preparation time fields—\"PRZYGOTOWANTE\" and \"GOTOMANTE\" instead of the correct Polish words—so I'll need to use fuzzy matching to catch these variations. Now I'm laying out the concrete improvements: I'll add Polish metadata patterns for serving sizes like \"NA OKOŁO 1 ½ KG\" and \"DLA 4 OSOB\" to the detection logic, then implement fuzzy matching for the preparation and cooking time fields to handle these OCR errors. Writing regex patterns...\n\nActually, using stem matching with wildcards feels too loose. I should step back — the core insight is that any ALL_CAPS line with a number that appears outside the opening section is probably metadata, not a dish title. But that rule would incorrectly flag legitimate dishes without numbers. Instead, I'll stick with explicit Polish prep patterns and handle OCR variations through flexible matching on the key word stems.\n\nAdding these specific patterns with OCR tolerance...\n\nStill writing regex patterns... I should also add a tiebreaker to the structural heading selection when scores are close—using position or word count to favor earlier or longer candidates, since the embedding rankings alone aren't always reliable. Let me verify this approach works on the new test cases before finalizing.\n\nLooking at the Kimchi example, my fixes should handle the metadata patterns like \"NA OKOŁO 1 ½ KG\" correctly, and the structural heading logic needs to account for single-word ALL_CAPS entries like \"SKŁADNIKI\" that don't meet the minimum word count threshold, while also being careful with edge cases like \"I PIKLE\" where one word is just a single letter.\n\nThe bilingual detection should kick in when \"Kimchi z ogórków\" and \"OI-SOBAGI\" have high embedding similarity, suppressing the Korean romanization and letting the Polish title win.\n\nNow moving to the second recipe, I'm checking \"Wiosna\" — it's mixed case and a single word, so it passes the initial filters, but I need to verify whether it's actually garbled or a legitimate title word.\n\nThen \"/ Warzywa\" gets merged with the preceding line since it starts with a slash, creating \"Wiosna / Warzywa\". The line \"DLA 4 OSOB\" gets filtered out as metadata using the pattern I added. I'm continuing through the remaining lines to evaluate them.\n\nNow I'm looking at \"ODE PORY DUSZONE W PIWIE\" — it's all caps with five words, so it's the title. \"PRZYGOTOWANTE 20 MIN\" is an OCR error that my pattern for \"PRZYGOTO\" followed by digits would catch. But \"GOTOMANTE 15 MIN\" is trickier — it's so corrupted that a simple prefix pattern won't match it, and I'm trying to figure out if a looser pattern would work without creating false positives.\n\nLet me trace through the hard filters for \"GOTOMANTE 15 MIN\" — it's 16 characters so it passes length, \"min\" isn't in the measurement patterns so it fails the ingredient check, it doesn't start with a number, and the garbled text detector is looking at vowel ratios and word structure to see if this should be filtered out.\n\nThe real issue is that this passes through as a candidate even though it's clearly cooking time metadata that got mangled by OCR. While it won't win as a structural heading since \"MIN\" is too short, I should add a more targeted filter that catches time-like patterns in all-caps text — something that looks for a number followed by time units like \"MIN\" or \"GODZ\".\n\nRefining the regex pattern to be more comprehensive...\n\nThis would catch all the cooking time variations regardless of OCR errors in the prefix. The challenge is making sure recipe titles themselves don't accidentally match this pattern, but the time unit suffix should be specific enough to avoid false positives. I'm settling on a regex pattern that catches time metadata like \"30 MIN\" or \"1 GODZ\" anywhere in a line, plus Polish serving indicators like \"NA 4\" or \"DLA 6\" at the start. Since lines starting with digits are already filtered out for titles, matching `\\d+\\s*MIN` is safe and won't accidentally catch legitimate recipe names. Now I'm thinking through potential edge cases — like whether these patterns could cause false positives or regressions when applied to the full extraction pipeline. Risk: Could filter legitimate titles containing \"NA\" or \"DLA\" at the start. E.g., \"NA ZDROWIE\" (To health) as a recipe name? Very unlikely.\n- Risk: Time-unit pattern `\\d+\\s*MIN` could filter titles with \"MIN\" in them. \"MINESTRONE\" has \"MIN\" but not preceded by a digit. \"5 MINUTE BREAD\" starts with digit → already filtered. Safe.\n\n**Fix 2 (Sub-section header removal before dedup):**\n- Risk: Could remove a legitimate short title if it's a substring of a multi-line join that shouldn't exist. But we're gating on \"followed by ingredient lines\", which is a strong signal.\n- What about ARAYES SHRAK? \"ARAYES\" is a prefix of \"ARAYES SHRAK\", but the existing prefix filter at line 440 already handles this case, and the new sub-section filter would just add another layer of protection.\n- For Finnish flatbreads like \"FINNISH MILK FLATBREADS\" and \"FINNISH POTATO FLATBREADS\", neither is a substring of the other, so the sub-section filter wouldn't trigger.\n\nThese fixes look solid, so I'm ready to write out the plan.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1403,"cache_read_input_tokens":49633,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1403},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"f1cce918-fde6-46b5-9093-50476190ee9c","uuid":"5fb65015-f64b-4ee3-88d6-0b30064eebbb"}
